l Whitburn |year= 1993 |title= Top Adult Contemporary: 1961\u20131993 |publisher= Record Research |page=24}}</ref>\n|align=\"center\"|27\n|-\n|US ''[[Cashbox (magazine)|Cash Box]]'' Top 100<ref>{{cite web|url=http://50.6.195.142/archives/70s_files/19761023.html |title=Archived copy |access-date=2015-06-09 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150518092327/http://50.6.195.142/archives/70s_files/19761023.html |archive-date=2015-05-18 |df= }}</ref>\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|8\n|}\n{{col-2}}\n\n====Year-end charts====\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Chart (1976)\n! Rank\n|-\n| Australia<ref>{{cite web|author=Steffen Hung |url=http://australian-charts.com/forum.asp?todo=viewthread&id=35092 |title=Forum - 1970 (ARIA Charts: Special Occasion Charts) |website=Australian-charts.com |date= |access-date=2016-09-27 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160602084720/http://australian-charts.com/forum.asp?todo=viewthread&id=35092 |archive-date=2016-06-02 |df= }}</ref>\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|58\n|-\n| Canada<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.collectionscanada.gc.ca/rpm/ |title=RPM - Library and Archives Canada &#124; RPM - Biblioth\u00e8que et Archives Canada |website=Collectionscanada.gc.ca |date= |access-date=2016-09-27 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160801033457/http://www.collectionscanada.gc.ca/rpm/ |archive-date=2016-08-01 |url-status=dead |df= }}</ref>\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|82\n|-\n|Netherlands <ref>[Top 100-Jaaroverzicht van 1976 Top 100-Jaaroverzicht van 1976]</ref>\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|80\n|-\n| New Zealand<ref>{{cite web|url=http://nztop40.co.nz/chart/?chart=3865 |title=Top Selling Singles of 1976 &#124; The Official New Zealand Music Chart |website=Nztop40.co.nz |date=1963-12-08 |accessdate=2016-09-27}}</ref>\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|49\n|-\n| UK<ref>{{cite journal |title=Top 50 Singles of 1976 |periodical=[[Music Week]] |publisher=Spotlight Publications |location=London, England |page=25 |date=25 December 1976}}</ref>\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|49\n|}\n{{col-end}}\n\n==The Tourists version==\n{{Infobox song\n| name       = I Only Wanna Be with You\n| cover      =\n| alt        =\n| border     = yes\n| type       = single\n| artist     = [[The Tourists]]\n| album      = [[Reality Effect]]\n| released   = November 1979\n| format     =\n| recorded   =\n| studio     =\n| venue      =\n| genre      = [[Pop music|Pop]]\n| length     =\n| label      = [[Logo Records|Logo]]\n| writer     = Mike Hawker, [[Ivor Raymonde]]\n| producer   =\n| chronology = Tourists\n| prev_title = The Lonliest Man in the World\n| prev_year  = 1979\n| next_title = So Good to Be Back Home Again\n| next_year  = 1980\n}}\n\n===Background===\nIn 1979, the song was also covered by [[The Tourists]], a band which included [[Annie Lennox]] on vocals. This was the band's biggest hit. The song was used on a montage of stars when [[Thames Television]] went off the air in 1992.\n\n===Chart performance===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n!Chart (1979\u201380)\n!Peak<br />position\n|-\n|[[Kent Music Report|Australian Singles Chart]]<ref>{{cite book|first=David|last=Kent|authorlink=David Kent (historian)|title=Australian Chart Book 1970\u20131992|publisher=Australian Chart Book|location=St Ives, N.S.W.|year=1993|page=311|isbn= 0-646-11917-6}}</ref>\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|6\n|-\n|[[Canadian Singles Chart]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|50\n|-\n|[[Irish Singles Chart]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://irishcharts.ie/search/placement?page=1&placement[artist]=Tourists|title=The Irish Charts \u2013 All there is to know > Search results for 'Tourists'|publisher=Fireball Media|accessdate=2016-11-16}}</ref>\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|13\n|-\n|[[UK Singles Chart]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.officialcharts.com/artist/17717/tourists/|title=Official Charts > Tourists|publisher=[[Official Charts Company|The Official UK Charts Company]]|accessdate=2016-11-16}}</ref>\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|4\n|-\n|U.S. [[Billboard Hot 100|''Billboard'' Hot 100]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.billboard.com/artist/419304/tourists/chart|title=Billboard > Artists / The Tourists > Chart History > The Hot 100|publisher=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|accessdate=2016-11-16}}</ref>\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|83\n|}\n\n==Nicolette Larson version==\n{{Infobox song\n| name       = I Only Want to Be with You\n| cover      = \n| alt        =\n| type       = single\n| artist     = [[Nicolette Larson]]\n| album      = [[All Dressed Up and No Place to Go|All Dressed Up <br/> and No Place to Go]]\n| B-side     = How Can We Go On\n| released   = July 1982\n| format     = 7\" 45 rpm\n| recorded   = \n| studio     = [[Sunset Sound Recorders|Sunset Sound]]\n| venue      =\n| genre      = [[Soft rock]]\n| length     = 3:16\n| label      = [[Warner Records|WB]]\n| writer     = [[Mike Hawker]], <br/> [[Ivor Raymonde]]\n| producer   = [[Andrew Gold]]\n| prev_title = Fool Me Again\n| prev_year  = 1981\n| next_title = Only Love Will Make Love Right\n| next_year  = 1985\n}}\n\n[[Nicolette Larson]] remade \"I Only Want to Be with You\" for her album ''[[All Dressed Up and No Place to Go]]'' produced by [[Andrew Gold]] and recorded  October 1981 - January 1982 at [[Sunset Sound Recorders|Sunset Sound]]. Released as a single in July 1982 - parallel with the album's release - Larson's version featured as [[A-side and B-side#B-side|B-side]] \"How Can We Go On\", a track from Larson's 1981 album ''[[Radioland (album)|Radioland]]'' which had been an unsuccessful 1981 [[A-side and B-side#A-side|A-side]] release.\n\nReviewing ''All Dressed Up and No Place to Go'', ''[[High Fidelity (magazine)|High Fidelity]]'' critic [[Steven Rea|Steven X. Rea]] cited \"[[Dusty Springfield]]'s 60's gem 'I Only Want to Be with You'\" as one of several tracks which \"Nicolette sings in an awkward warble, devoid of any emotional range\":<ref>''High Fidelity'' September 1982 \"Backbeat - Reviews\" by Steven X. Rea p.76-77</ref> Larson's \"I Only Want to Be with You\" drew similarly dismissive reaction from Tom Long of the ''Santa Cruz Sentinel'', who rated the original 1963 hit a \"swell oldie [that's an] ingratiating piece of fluff\" and Larson's remake \"awful [although] despite uninspired vocals and sheet musicianship [it] sounds good on the radio simply because the song itself sounds good and tickles forotten memory synapses\",<ref>''Santa Cruz Sentinel'' 27 August 1982 \"Records\" by Tom Long p.24</ref> and also Bill Provick of the ''Ottawa Citizen'' who opined Larson gave \"a rather lacklustre reading of [a] normally effervescent pop-rock classic.\"<ref>''Ottawa Citizen'' 10 September 1982 \"Revolutions\" by Bill Provick p71.</ref> Tim Gebhart of the ''Rapid City Journal'' was more positive: \"Larson['s] version remains true to the original but also contains her own special touch in the vocals.\"<ref>''Rapid City Journal'' 20 August 1982 \"Sounds '82\" by Tim Gebhart p.V-5</ref>\n\nDespite becoming Larson's fourth single to rank on the [[Billboard Hot 100|Hot 100]] chart in ''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]'' magazine - and her first Hot 100 entry since 1980 - \"I Only Want to Be with You\" would prove a [[Top 40]] shortfall stalling at #53 in September 1983. Larson's label [[Warner Records|WB Records]], electing not to issue a second single from ''All Dressed Up and No Place to Go'', were motivated by the underperformance of that album and its one single to end Larson's label tenure. Larson would have one subsequent major label affiliation, having two [[country music|C&W]]-focused albums released by [[MCA Records]] in 1985-86.\n\n==Samantha Fox version==\n{{Infobox song\n| name       = I Only Wanna Be with You\n| cover      = I Only Wanna Be With You single cover - Samantha Fox.jpg\n| alt        =\n| border     = yes\n| caption    = 12-inch single cover\n| type       = single\n| artist     = [[Samantha Fox]]\n| album      = [[I Wanna Have Some Fun]]\n| B-side     = Confession\n| released   = January 1989\n| format     =\n* [[7-inch single|7-inch]]\n* [[12-inch single|12-inch]]\n* [[CD single|CD]]\n* [[Mini CD single|mini CD]]\n| recorded   = \n| studio     = PWL, The Borough, London\n| genre      = [[Pop music|Pop]]<ref>{{Allmusic|class=album|id=r7692}}</ref>\n| length     = 2:45\n| label      = [[Jive Records|Jive]]\n| writer     =\n* Mike Hawker\n* [[Ivor Raymonde]]\n| producer   = [[Stock Aitken Waterman]]\n| chronology = Samantha Fox\n| prev_title = [[I Wanna Have Some Fun (song)|I Wanna Have Some Fun]]\n| prev_year  = 1988\n| next_title = (Hurt Me, Hurt Me) But the Pants Stay On\n| next_year  = 1991\n| misc       = {{External music video|{{YouTube|EYFXLL09_9w|\"I Only Want to Be with You\"}}}}\n}}\n\nIn 1988, English singer [[Samantha Fox]] covered the song as \"I Only Wanna Be with You\" for her third studio album, ''[[I Wanna Have Some Fun]]'' (1988).\n\nFox would recall the song as being the first song she ever learned to sing, the Dusty Springfield original version being among a stack of singles her mother handed down to Fox when Fox was aged ten.<ref>''Honolulu Star-Bulletin'' 8 June 1989 \"Music Fans Have Pick of Sweet Sounds: three artists serve up pop & soulful fare in three venues\" by John Berger p.E-1</ref>\n\nReleased as the follow-up single to the [[I Wanna Have Some Fun (song)|album's title cut]], \"I Only Wanna Be With You\" was promoted with a music video which included scenes of Fox hunting through trash cans, dancing, fireworks, and the singer in bed with her bespectacled lover.<ref>{{YouTube|rvNn0srhdIQ}}{{dead link|date=October 2012}}</ref> Fox also promoted the song via televised performances, including those on ''[[Top of the Pops]]'' in 1989 and ''Viva el espect\u00e1culo'' on [[TVE1]] in 1990.<ref>[https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0741670/ \"Viva el espect\u00e1culo\" Episode #1.15 (TV episode 1990) - IMDb<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=h0VwQCpC-8A |title=Samantha Fox - I Only Wanna Be With You (TOTP '89) |publisher=YouTube |date= |accessdate=2012-10-01}}</ref>\n\n\"I Only Wanna Be with You\" essentially earned Fox her final global hit single. In the United States, where \"I Wanna Have Some Fun\" had been a Top Ten hit, \"I Only Wanna Be with You\" rose no higher than number 31 and would mark Fox's final [[Billboard Hot 100|''Billboard'' Hot 100]] appearance: in Fox's native UK her version outperformed her previous six single releases with a number-16 peak, but would also become Fox' final major hit bar her 1998 one-off comeback single \"[[Santa Maria (Tatjana song)|Santa Maria]]\".\n\n===Track listings===\n*'''7-inch single'''<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.discogs.com/Samantha-Fox-I-Only-Wanna-Be-With-You/release/765727 |title=Samantha Fox - I Only Wanna Be With You (Vinyl) at Discogs |publisher=Discogs.com |date= |accessdate=2012-10-01}}</ref>\n:A. \"I Only Wanna Be with You\" \u2013 2:45\n:B. \"Confession\" \u2013 4:40\n\n*'''12-inch single'''<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.discogs.com/Samantha-Fox-I-Only-Wanna-Be-With-You/release/299989 |title=Samantha Fox - I Only Wanna Be With You (Vinyl) at Discogs |publisher=Discogs.com |date= |accessdate=2012-10-01}}</ref>\n:A1. \"I Only Wanna Be with You\" (Extended Mix) \u2013 4:56\n:A2. \"I Only Wanna Be with You\" (Acapella Mix) \u2013 3:17\n:B1. \"I Only Wanna Acid with You\" (Mix 1) \u2013 6:20\n:B2. \"Confession\" \u2013 4:40\n\n*'''European CD single'''\n#\"I Only Wanna Be with You\" \u2013 2:45\n#\"[[Nothing's Gonna Stop Me Now (Samantha Fox song)|Nothing's Gonna Stop Me Now]]\" \u2013 3:42\n#\"I Only Wanna Be with You\" (Extended Version) \u2013 4:56\n#\"Confession\" \u2013 4:40\n\n*'''Japanese mini CD single'''\n#\"I Only Wanna Be with You\"\n#\"The Best Is Yet to Come\"\n\n===Charts===\n{{col-begin}}\n{{col-2}}\n\n====Weekly charts====\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable plainrowheaders\" style=\"text-align:center\"\n|-\n! scope=\"col\"| Chart (1989)\n! scope=\"col\"| Peak<br />position\n|-\n{{single chart|Australia|19|artist=Samantha Fox|song=I Only Wanna Be with You|rowheader=true|accessdate=17 March 2020}}\n|-\n{{single chart|Austria|19|artist=Samantha Fox|song=I Only Wanna Be with You|rowheader=true|accessdate=17 March 2020}}\n|-\n{{single chart|Flanders|1|artist=Samantha Fox|song=I Only Wanna Be with You|rowheader=true|accessdate=17 March 2020}}\n|-\n{{single chart|Canadatopsingles|29|chartid=6352|rowheader=true|accessdate=17 March 2020}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| Europe ([[European Hot 100 Singles]])<ref>{{cite magazine |url=https://www.americanradiohistory.com/UK/Music-and-Media/80s/1989/M&M-1989-03-11.pdf |title=Eurochart Hot 100 Singles |magazine=[[Music & Media]] |volume=6 |issue=10 |date=11 March 1989 |page=25<!-- 18 in PDF file --> |oclc=29800226 |accessdate=17 March 2020 |via=American Radio History}}</ref>\n| 27\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| Finland ([[The Official Finnish Charts|Suomen virallinen lista]])<ref>{{cite book |last=Pennanen |first=Timo |title=Sis\u00e4lt\u00e4\u00e4 hitin \u2013 levyt ja esitt\u00e4j\u00e4t Suomen musiikkilistoilla vuodesta 1972 |language=Finnish |edition=1st |location=Helsinki |publisher=[[Otava (publisher)|Kustannusosakeyhti\u00f6 Otava]] |year=2006 |isbn=978-951-1-21053-5}}</ref>\n| 4\n|-\n{{single chart|France|10|artist=Samantha Fox|song=I Only Wanna Be with You|rowheader=true|accessdate=17 March 2020}}\n|-\n{{single chart|Ireland2|9|song=I Only Wanna Be with You|rowheader=true|accessdate=17 March 2020|refname=IEFox}}\n|-\n{{single chart|Dutch40|11|artist=Samantha Fox|rowheader=true|accessdate=17 March 2020}}\n|-\n{{single chart|Dutch100|13|artist=Samantha Fox|song=I Only Wanna Be with You|rowheader=true|accessdate=17 March 2020}}\n|-\n{{single chart|New Zealand|28|artist=Samantha Fox|song=I Only Wanna Be with You|rowheader=true|accessdate=17 March 2020}}\n|-\n{{single chart|Switzerland|24|artist=Samantha Fox|song=I Only Wanna Be with You|rowheader=true|accessdate=17 March 2020}}\n|-\n{{single chart|UKsinglesbyname|16|artist=Samantha Fox|artistid=23153|rowheader=true|accessdate=17 March 2020}}\n|-\n{{single chart|Billboardhot100|31|artist=Samantha Fox|rowheader=true|accessdate=17 March 2020}}\n|-\n{{single chart|Billboarddanceclubplay|46|artist=Samantha Fox|rowheader=true|accessdate=17 March 2020}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| US [[Hot Dance Singles Sales]] (''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]'')<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.billboard.com/music/samantha-fox/chart-history/DSA |title=Samantha Fox Chart History (Dance Singles Sales) |work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]] |accessdate=17 March 2020}}</ref>\n| 12\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| US ''[[Cashbox (magazine)|Cash Box]]'' Top 100<ref>{{cite web |url=https://cashboxmagazine.com/archives/80s_files/19890520.html |title=Cash Box Top 100 Singles \u2013 Week ending May 20, 1989 |work=[[Cashbox (magazine)|Cash Box]] |accessdate=17 March 2020}}</ref>\n| 38\n|-\n{{single chart|West Germany|25|songid=1932|artist=Samantha Fox|song=I Only Wanna Be with You|rowheader=true|accessdate=17 March 2020}}\n|}\n{{col-2}}\n\n====Year-end charts====\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable plainrowheaders\" style=\"text-align:center\"\n|-\n! scope=\"col\"| Chart (1989)\n! scope=\"col\"| Position\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| Belgium (Ultratop 50 Flanders)<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.ultratop.be/nl/annual.asp?year=1989&cat=s |title=Jaaroverzichten 1989 \u2013 Singles |language=Dutch |publisher=Ultratop |accessdate=17 March 2020}}</ref>\n| 21\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| Netherlands (Dutch Top 40)<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.top40.nl/bijzondere-lijsten/top-100-jaaroverzichten/1989 |title=Top 100-Jaaroverzicht van 1989 |language=Dutch |publisher=Dutch Top 40 |accessdate=17 March 2020}}</ref>\n| 97\n|}\n{{col-end}}\n\n==Luis Miguel version==\n{{Infobox song\n| name       = Ahora te puedes marchar\n| cover      = Ahoratepuedesmarchar.jpg\n| alt        =\n| type       = single\n| artist     = [[Luis Miguel]]\n| album      = [[Soy como quiero ser]]\n| B-side     = Sunny\n| released   = {{Start date|1987}}\n| format     = [[Airplay]] \u00b7 [[Promo single]]\n| recorded   = 1986-1987 <br/>Record One <br/>([[Sherman Oaks, Los Angeles|Sherman Oaks, California]]) <br/>Metropolis Studios<br/>George Tobin Studios<br/>Sunset Sound Studios <br/>([[Hollywood|Hollywood, California]])</small>\n| studio     =\n| venue      =\n| genre      = [[Latin music (genre)|Latin]]\n| length     = 3:15\n| label      = [[Warner Music Group|WEA Latina]]\n| writer     = Mike Hawker \u00b7 [[Ivor Raymonde]] \u00b7 Luis G\u00f3mez Escolar\n| producer   = Juan Carlos Calder\u00f3n\n| prev_title = [[Fiebre de Amor (album)|Todo el amor del mundo]]\n| prev_year  = 1986\n| next_title = No me puedo escapar de t\u00ed\n| next_year  = 1987\n}}\n\n===Background===\n[[Mexican people|Mexican]] singer [[Luis Miguel]] recorded a version of the song, titled '''\"Ahora te puedes marchar\"''' (\"Now you can leave\") which was released as the first single from his Grammy-nominated album ''[[Soy Como Quiero Ser|Soy como quiero ser]]'' (1987), the first album recorded by the singer under the [[Warner Music|WEA]] record label. It was produced by [[Juan Carlos Calder\u00f3n]] and adapted by Luis G\u00f3mez Escolar.<ref>{{cite web |title=Soy Como Quiero Ser |work=Allmusic |publisher=Macromedia Corporation |url={{Allmusic|class=album|id=r100918|pure_url=yes}} |accessdate=2009-04-30 }}</ref> This single became very successful, peaking at number-one in the [[Hot Latin Tracks|''Billboard'' Hot Latin Tracks chart]] for three non-consecutive weeks in 1987, being the first chart topper for the singer on the chart.<ref>{{cite web |title=Luis Miguel - Charts & Awards |work=Allmusic |publisher=Macromedia Corporation |url={{Allmusic|class=artist|id=p40380|pure_url=yes}} |accessdate=2009-04-30 }}</ref> At the time, Luis Miguel was the youngest to score a number-one hit on the Hot Latin Tracks at the age of 17, ironically replacing the then 44-year-old veteran [[Julio Iglesias]] at the summit. In 2005, Luis Miguel included this song on his compilation album ''[[Grandes \u00c9xitos (Luis Miguel album)|Grandes \u00c9xitos]]''.<ref>{{cite web |title=Grandes \u00c9xitos - Luis Miguel |work=Allmusic |publisher=Macromedia Corporation |url={{Allmusic|class=album|id=r810980|pure_url=yes}} |accessdate=2009-04-30 }}</ref> This version ranked at number 28 in the [[Hot Latin Tracks Year-End Chart of 1988]]. The song was translated into Portuguese as \"Agora Voc\u00ea Pode Ir\" for the Brazilian edition of the album.<ref name=\"soycomoquierserbr\">{{cite AV media notes | title= Soy Como Quiero Ser|others=Luis Miguel|location=Brazil | year=1987 | publisher=Warner Music Brasil|id=670.0124}}</ref>\n\nThe lyrics are considerably different from the original song as long as the song relates about a guy rejecting a girl that is wanting to reform a relationship rather than the unconditional love shown in Dusty Springfield version.\n\n===Music videos===\nTwo music videos were shot. The first one was shot with [[Ang\u00e9lica Rivera]], while the second one was shot dancing in a bridge. The second one was included in [[Grandes \u00c9xitos (Luis Miguel album)|Grandes \u00c9xitos Videos]].\n\n===Chart performance===\n====Weekly charts====\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n!Chart (1987)\n!Peak<br />position\n|-\n| Spain ([[PROMUSICAE]])\n| style =\"text-align:center;\"|1\n|-\n| US ''Billboard'' [[Hot Latin Tracks]]<ref>{{cite web |title=Luis Miguel-Chart History: Hot Latin Songs |url=https://www.billboard.com/music/Luis-Miguel/chart-history/HTL |website=Billboard |publisher=Prometheus Global Media |accessdate=7 December 2019}}</ref>\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|1\n|}\n\n====Year-end charts====\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n!Chart (1987)\n!Peak<br />position\n|-\n| US ''Billboard'' [[Hot Latin Tracks]]<ref name=\"hlt87\">{{cite journal| last =| first =| date = 1987-12-26| title = 1987 the year in music: Hot Latin Tracks| journal = Billboard| publisher = Nielsen Business Media, Inc.| volume =| issue =| page = YE-45| url =https://books.google.com/books?id=JCgEAAAAMBAJ&dq=billboard&q=latin#v=onepage&q&f=false| accessdate = 2011-01-04}}</ref>\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|11\n|}\n\n==Other versions==\n{{columns-start|num=2}}\n'''1964''' [[Les Surfs]] as \"A pr\u00e9sent tu peux t'en aller'\" <small>French</small> also recorded by [[Richard Anthony (French singer)|Richard Anthony]] And Claudette Vandal\n* [[Les Surfs]] as \"E adesso te ne puoi andar\" #2 (Italy)\n* [[Lill-Babs]] as \"Jag Vill Vara N\u00e4ra Dig\" <small>Swedish</small>\n* Donna Lynn on her eponymous album Capitol LP 2085\n* [[Lita Torell\u00f3]] ([[:es:Lita Torell\u00f3|es]]) as \"Ahora te puedes marchar\" <small>Spanish</small> also recorded by [[Silvana Velasco]] ([[:es:Silvana Velasco|es]])\n'''1965''' [[Enrique Guzm\u00e1n]] on his album ''\u00c9xitos internacionales'' as \"S\u00f3lo quiero estar contigo\" <small>Spanish</small> also recorded by [[Juan Ram\u00f3n (singer)|Juan Ram\u00f3n]] ([[:es:Juan Ram\u00f3n|es]]) on his album ''M\u00e1s coraz\u00f3n que nunca''<br/>\n'''1966''' [[Les Surfs]] as \"Ahora te puedes marchar\" <small>Spanish</small><br/>\n'''1967''' [[Helena Vondr\u00e1\u010dkov\u00e1]] as \"Chytila jsem na pasece mot\u00fdlka\" <small>Czech</small><br/>\n'''1969''' Elin as \"Det har jeg altid \u00f8nsket mig\" <small>Danish</small>\n* Agneta Zel\u00e1n as \"Jag Ville Vara N\u00e4ra Dig\" <small>Swedish</small>\n'''1975''' [[Chelsia Chan]] on her debut album ''Dark Side Of Your Mind''\n* [[Rauli Somerjoki|Rauli 'Badding' Somerjoki]] on his album ''Syd\u00e4n l\u00e4mp\u00f6\u00e4 t\u00e4ys'' as  \n:\"[[Jykev\u00e4\u00e4 on rakkaus]]\" <small>Finnish</small>\n'''1976''' [[Howard Carpendale]] as \"Ab Heute Weht Ein Neuer Wind\" <small>German</small>\n* [[:zh:\u99ae\u5049\u68e0|James Fung]] as \"\u5929\u8cdc\u826f\u7de3\" <small>Cantonese</small>\n'''1977''' [[Pink Lady (duo)|Pink Lady]] as {{nihongo4|\"Futaridake no Date\"|\u4e8c\u4eba\u3060\u3051\u306e\u30c7\u30fc\u30c8||\"Date for Two\"}} on their debut album ''[[Pepper Keibu (album)|Pepper Keibu]]'' <small>Japanese</small>\n\n'''1982''' [[Barbara Dickson]] on her album ''Here We Go...Barbara Dickson Live on Tour''\n:<small>in [[medley (music)|medley]] with \"[[Dancing in the Street]]\"/ \"[[He's a Rebel]]\"/ \"[[You Keep Me Hangin' On]]\"</small>\n'''1983''' [[The Flirts]] on their album ''[[Flirts]]''\n* [[Tony Hatch]] & His Orchestra on his album ''Quiet Nights''\n'''1986''' [[Southside Johnny & The Jukes]] on their album ''At Least We Got Shoes''\n* Thea Paluoja & Proov 583 as \"Sinu juures\" <small>Estonian</small>\n'''1989''' [[Danny Chan]] on his album ''[[Yat sang ho kau]]''<br /> \n:as \"\u6d41\u6d6a\u8005/ lau long tze\" <small>Cantonese</small> <br/>\n'''1991''' [[Maywood (band)|Maywood]] on their ''Walking Back to Happiness'' album<br/>\n'''1992''' [[Paula Koivuniemi]]  on her album ''Se kes\u00e4ni mun'' as \"Haluun olla luonas sun\" <small>Finnish</small>\n* [[Wencke Myhre|Wenche Myhre]] as \"Hvis Bare Jeg F\u00e5r Bli Hos Deg\" <small>Norwegian</small>\n\n'''1993''' [[Beatriz Rico]]  on her album ''Baila sin parar'' as \"Ahora te puedes marchar\" <small>Spanish</small><br/>\n'''1997''' [[Ash (band)|Ash]] covered the song for a promotional tour<ref>{{cite web|url=http://eil.com/shop/moreinfo.asp?catalogid=310069 |title=Ash 7\" info |publisher=Eil.com |date=2004-11-18 |accessdate=2012-10-01}}</ref>\n\n{{column}}\n\n'''1998''' [[Twiggy]] & [[Twiggy Ramirez|Twiggy]] on the soundtrack of ''[[Dead Man on Campus]]''\n* [[:da:Annette Klingenberg|Annette Klingenberg]] on her album ''Weep No More''\n'''1999''' [[Argema (band)|Argema]] ([[:cs:Argema|cs]]) on their album ''Milion Sn\u016f'' as \"\u017d\u00e1ba\"<small>Czech</small>\n*[[Elton John]] performed the song in concert at the [[Peoria Civic Center|Peoria (IL) Civic Center]] Arena after learning of Dusty Springfield's death on March 2, 1999. John introduced the song saying \"Dusty, wherever you are, this one's for you, my love, with all my love.\"\n*[[Ville Valo]] with the [[Agents (Finnish band)|Agents]] on the Agents' album ''Laulava Syd\u00e4n'' as \"[[Jykev\u00e4\u00e4 on rakkaus]]\" <small>Finnish</small>\n'''2000''' [[Ren\u00e9 Froger]] on his album ''The Passion Tracks'' <br/>\n'''2001''' [[Me First and the Gimme Gimmes]] on their album ''[[Blow in the Wind]]''<br/>\n'''2002''' [[Vonda Shepard]] on her album ''[[Songs from Ally McBeal]]''<br/>\n'''2003''' {{ill|Maleewan Jemina|th|\u0e21\u0e32\u0e25\u0e35\u0e27\u0e31\u0e25\u0e22\u0e4c \u0e40\u0e08\u0e21\u0e35\u0e19\u0e48\u0e32|lt=|WD=}} on her 2003 album ''Me & Moment in Time''<br/>\n'''2004''' [[Tomoko Kawase|Tommy February<sup>6</sup>]] on her single \"[[Lovely (Yumemiru Lovely Boy)]]\" <br/>\n'''2005''' [[Taiwan]]ese female group [[7 Flowers]] on their eponymous album \n* [[Volbeat (band)|Volbeat]] on their 2005 debut album ''[[The Strength / The Sound / The Songs]]''\n* [[Susan Wong]] on her album ''These Foolish Things''\n'''2007''' [[Tina Arena]] on her album ''[[Songs of Love & Loss]]''\n* The Shakers (Uruguayan band) as \"S\u00f3lo quiero estar contigo\" <small>Spanish</small>: \n:bonus track on re-issue of band's 1965 album ''Los Shakers''\n'''2008''' [[Shelby Lynne]] on her Dusty Springfield [[tribute album]] ''[[Just a Little Lovin' (Shelby Lynne album)|Just a Little Lovin']]''<br/>\n'''2009''' [[Jessica Andersson]] as \"I Only Wanna Be With You\" on her album ''[[Wake Up (Jessica Andersson album)|Wake Up]]'' \n* [[Bata Adrienn|Barbee]] ([[:hu:Bata Adrienn|hu]]) as \"\u00c1mor nyila\" <small>Hungarian</small>\n'''2011''' [[Amy Macdonald]]: recorded 2008 for canceled multi-artist Dusty Springfield tribute album: track first released on album ''[[Reworked (charity compilation album)|Reworked]]'', a multi-artist fundraiser for [[Save the Children]] featuring songs used in [[John Lewis (department store)|John Lewis]] ad campaigns <br/>\n'''2013''' [[Lodovica Comello]] on her album ''Universo''<br/>\n'''2018''' [[Super Junior]] as \"Ahora te puedes marchar\" <small>Spanish</small> on their [[One More Time (EP)|''One More Time'' EP]]<br/>\n''2019''' [[Emma Bunton]] on her album ''[[My Happy Place]]'' as a duet with [[Will Young]]<ref>https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/pop/8500161/emma-bunton-announces-my-happy-place-album</ref>\n\u2018\u2019\u20192019\u2019\u2019\u2019\nLYRA \n\n{{columns-end}}\n\n==Uses on television==\n* Was used in the opening for the TV series ''[[Arliss|Arli$$]]''.\n* [[The Tourists]]' version of the song was played along with TV clips on final week of broadcasting of [[Thames Television]] in December 1992 before [[Carlton Television]] took over.\n* The song was used in the [[United Kingdom|British]] [[soap opera]] ''[[EastEnders]]'' when the character [[Sam Mitchell (EastEnders)|Sam Mitchell]] dug up the body of [[Den Watts]].\n* The song was used by [[TVNZ]]'s [[TV2 (New Zealand)|TV2]] to promote their programming from 1997 to mid-2000, with the chorus changing its words to \"You only want to be with 2\".\n* The song was also used as soundtrack in [[Greeks|Greek]] [[Comedy]] [[Television series|TV series]] \"Tilempora\" (TV Storm) on [[Mega Channel]] in 2004.\n* The song was used by [[CBC Television]] to promote its programming between 1989 and 1991, while the network's slogan was \"CBC and you\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=emkjQ2cr3Zc |title=CBC & You 1990 |publisher=[[YouTube]] |date= |accessdate=2016-09-27}}</ref>\n* The song featured in a [[John Lewis (department store)|John Lewis]] television ad highlighting how the company had been selling electronic equipment for a substantial number of years.\n* The song was used in a swimwear advert for [[Boux Avenue]] in 2014. The ad featured [[Jamelia]], who also sang the song, with the chorus changed to \"I only want to be with Boux\".\n* A television ad campaign for [[Dogs Trust]] which launched in February 2016 features Hope Russell-Winter singing \"I Only Want to Be With You\".\n* The song was also featured in an episode of ''[[That '70s Show]]'' when Fez and Donna were having scenes where they pretended to be dating.\n* [[Me First And The Gimme Gimmes]]' version of the song was used in an episode of [[Shameless (U.S. TV series)|Shameless]] (USA).\n* Janine sings the song to her baby in the hospital in season 2, episode 8 of ''[[The Handmaid's Tale (TV series)|The Handmaid's Tale]]''.\n* A cover version of the song, played by a [[saxophonist]], serves as the theme tune to ''[[Kate & Koji]]''.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{MetroLyrics song|dusty-springfield|i-only-want-to-be-with-you}}<!-- Licensed lyrics provider -->\n* {{YouTube|osVaF4t-zFc|Listen to \"I Only Want to Be with You\" (Dusty Springfield)}}\n* {{YouTube|UtwAoHOUQ-E|Listen to \"I Only Want to Be with You\" (Bay City Rollers)}}\n\n{{Dusty Springfield}}\n{{Bay City Rollers}}\n{{Samantha Fox}}\n{{Luis Miguel singles}}\n{{The Tourists}}\n{{Nicolette Larson}}\n{{Stock Aitken Waterman}}\n\n[[Category:1963 debut singles]]\n[[Category:1987 singles]]\n[[Category:1989 singles]]\n[[Category:Luis Miguel songs]]\n[[Category:Dusty Springfield songs]]\n[[Category:Bay City Rollers songs]]\n[[Category:Song recordings with Wall of Sound arrangements]]\n[[Category:Nicolette Larson songs]]\n[[Category:Samantha Fox songs]]\n[[Category:Southside Johnny & The Asbury Jukes songs]]\n[[Category:Billboard Hot Latin Songs number-one singles]]\n[[Category:Song recordings produced by Jimmy Ienner]]\n[[Category:Song recordings produced by Stock Aitken Waterman]]\n[[Category:1963 songs]]\n[[Category:Song recordings produced by Johnny Franz]]\n[[Category:Philips Records singles]]\n[[Category:Jive Records singles]]\n[[Category:Arista Records singles]]\n[[Category:Bell Records singles]]\n[[Category:Ultratop 50 Singles (Flanders) number-one singles]]\n[[Category:Warner Music Latina singles]]\n[[Category:Warner Records singles]]\n[[Category:Songs written by Ivor Raymonde]]\n[[Category:Songs written by Mike Hawker (songwriter)]]\n", "name_user": "JGabbard", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eWeekly charts:+w", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/I_Only_Want_to_Be_with_You"}
{"title_page": "Achelous", "text_new": "{{other uses}}\n{{short description|Ancient Greek river god}}\n[[Image:Acheloos, detail of roman mosaic from Zeugma.jpg|thumb|300px|Achelous was often reduced to a bearded mask{{Citation needed|date=September 2017}}, an inspiration for the medieval [[Green Man]].{{fact|date=April 2020}} Floor mosaic, [[Zeugma, Commagene|Zeugma]], Turkey.]]\n<!-- leave redlink to prevent improper \"(genus)\" -->\n\nIn [[Greek mythology]], '''Achelous''' ({{IPAc-en|\u02cc|\u00e6|k|\u1d7b|\u02c8|l|o\u028a|.|\u0259|s}}; [[Ancient Greek]]: \u1f08\u03c7\u03b5\u03bb\u03ce\u03ca\u03bf\u03c2, and later {{lang|grc|\u1f08\u03c7\u03b5\u03bb\u1ff7\u03bf\u03c2}}, ''Akhel\u00f4ios'') was originally the god of all water<ref>Isler, pp. 12&ndash;36.</ref> and the rivers of the world were viewed by many as his sinews.<ref>Molinari and Sisci, pp. 60&ndash;62.</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|author=G. B. D'Alessio|title=Textual Fluctuations and Cosmic Streams: Ocean and Acheloios|journal=Journal of Hellenic Studies|publisher=The Council for the Society for the Promotion of Hellenic Studies|place=London|volume=124|year=2004|pages=20\u20131}}</ref> Later, in [[Hellenistic]] times, he was mostly relegated to the [[Achelous River]], which is the largest river of Greece, every river having its own river spirit.\n\nAchelous was also an important deity in [[Etruscan mythology]],<ref>{{Cite book|title=Acheloos: Eine Monographie|last=Isler|first=Hans Peter|publisher=Verlag|year=1970|isbn=|location=Bern|pages=|quote=|via=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Jannot|first=Jean-Rene|title=Acheloos, le taureau androcephale et les masques cornus dans l'Etrurie archaique|journal=Latomus|volume=33, 4}}</ref> intimately related to water as in the Greek tradition but also carrying significant [[chthonic]] associations. Man-faced bull iconography was first adapted to represent Achelous by the Etruscans in the 8th century BC, and the Greeks later adopted this same tradition.<ref>Molinari and Sisci, pp. 48&ndash;68.</ref>\n\n==Etymology==\nThe name \u1f08\u03c7\u03b5\u03bb\u03ce\u03ca\u03bf\u03c2 is possibly pre-Greek, its meaning is not entirely certain. Recent arguments suggest it is [[Semitic languages|Semitic]] in origin, with the initial \u0391\u03c7- stemming from the [[Akkadian (language)|Akkadian]] ''a\u1e2bu'' (\"bank of the river\"), or ''a\u1e2b\u00fb'' (\"seashore\") and the suffix -\u03b5\u03bb\u03ce\u1f34\u03bf\u03c2, from the Akkadian ''illu'' (\"watercourse\" or \"water of the river invading land\").<ref>Molinari and Sisci, pp. 93&ndash;95.</ref>\n\n==Genealogy==\n[[File:Hall of the Augustals.jpg|thumb|Hercules and Achelous in a Roman wall painting from the [[Augustales|Hall of the Augustales]].]]\n\nAccording to [[Hesiod]], Achelous, along with all the other [[Potamoi|river gods]], was the son of the Titans [[Oceanus]] and [[Tethys (mythology)|Tethys]].<ref>[[Hesiod]], ''[[Theogony]]'' [http://www.perseus.tufts.edu/hopper/text?doc=Hes.+Th.+337 337&ndash;345, 366&ndash;370].</ref> According to the sixth-century [[mythographer]] [[Acusilaus]], Achelous was the \"oldest and most honoured\" of the river-god offspring of Oceanus.<ref>Fowler 2103, pp. 12&ndash;13; Gantz, p. 28; Andolfi, fr. 1; [[Richard Claverhouse Jebb|Jebb]], [http://www.perseus.tufts.edu/hopper/text?doc=Perseus%3Atext%3A1999.04.0027%3Atext%3Dcomm%3Acommline%3D9 note on line 9]; Freeman, p. 16; [[Acusilaus]] [https://books.google.com/books?id=j0nRE4C2WBgC&pg=PA4 fr. 1 Fowler] [= [[FGrHist]] 2 1 = ''[[Vorsokr.]]'' 9 B 21 = [[Macrobius]], ''[[Saturnalia (Macrobius)|Saturnalia]]'' [https://www-loebclassics-com.ezproxy.bu.edu/view/macrobius-saturnalia/2011/pb_LCL511.425.xml 5.18.9&ndash;10]]. Compare with [[Hesiod]] ''[[Theogony]]'' [http://data.perseus.org/citations/urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0020.tlg001.perseus-eng1:337-370 361], [http://data.perseus.org/citations/urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0020.tlg001.perseus-eng1:767-806 777], and [[Aristotle]], ''[[Metaphysics]]'' [http://data.perseus.org/citations/urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0086.tlg025.perseus-eng1:1.983b 1.983b] where the river [[Styx]] is said to be the eldest (daughter) and most honored (Fowler 2013, p. 13).</ref> [[Maurus Servius Honoratus|Servius]] relating a tradition of unknown origin, reports that Achelous was said to have been the son of Earth (i.e. Gaia).<ref>Fowler, p. 12; [[Maurus Servius Honoratus|Servius]] on [[Virgil]]'s ''[[Georgics]]'' [http://www.perseus.tufts.edu/hopper/text?doc=Perseus%3Atext%3A2007.01.0092%3Abook%3D1%3Acommline%3D8 1.8].</ref>  According to the Renaissance, mythographer [[Natalis Comes]], [[Alcaeus of Mytilene|Alcaeus]] had Achelous as the son of Ocean and Earth.<ref>Alcaeus fr. 450, Campbell, p. 437.</ref>\n\nAchelous had various offspring.<ref>Parada, s.v. Achelous, p. 3.</ref> He was said to be the father of the [[Siren (mythology)|Siren]]s.<ref>Grimal, s.v. Sirens p. 421; Ker\u00e9nyi 1951, pp. 56, 58.</ref> According to the 3rd-century BC poet [[Lycophron]], the Sirens were the daughters of Achelous, by an unnamed \"melodious mother\" (perhaps meaning the mother was a [[Muse]]).<ref>[[Lycophron]], ''Alexandra'' [https://archive.org/stream/callimachuslycop00calluoft#page/552/mode/2up 712&ndash;716], with Mair's notes.</ref> Another 3rd-century BC poet Apollonius of Rhodes, makes the mother the Muse [[Terpsichore]],<ref>[[Apollonius of Rhodes]], ''[[Argonautica]]'' [http://www.archive.org/stream/argonautica00apoluoft#page/354/mode/2up 4.893].</ref> while according to other accounts, she was the Muse [[Melpomene]],<ref>[[Bibliotheca (Pseudo-Apollodorus)|Apollodorus]], [http://data.perseus.org/citations/urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0548.tlg001.perseus-eng1:1.3.4 1.3.4], [http://data.perseus.org/citations/urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0548.tlg002.perseus-eng1:e.7.18 E 7.18]; [[Hyginus]], ''[[Fabulae]]'' 125.13.</ref> or the [[Calydon]]ian princess [[Sterope]].<ref>[[Bibliotheca (Pseudo-Apollodorus)|Apollodorus]], [http://data.perseus.org/citations/urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0548.tlg001.perseus-eng1:1.7.10 1.7.10].</ref> [[Ovid]] calls the Sirens simply daughters of Achelous, with no mention of their mother.<ref>[[Ovid]], ''[[Metamorphoses]]'' [https://www-loebclassics-com.ezproxy.bu.edu/view/ovid-metamorphoses/1916/pb_LCL042.277.xml 5.552&ndash;555], [https://www-loebclassics-com.ezproxy.bu.edu/view/ovid-metamorphoses/1916/pb_LCL043.307.xml 14.87&ndash;88].</ref>\n\nBy [[Perimede (mythology)|Perimede]], the daughter of [[Aeolus (son of Hellen)|Aeolus]], Achelous was said to have fathered [[Hippodamas]] and [[Orestes (Greek myth)|Orestes]].<ref>Hard, [https://books.google.com/books?id=r1Y3xZWVlnIC&pg=PA410 p. 410]; [[Bibliotheca (Pseudo-Apollodorus)|Apollodorus]], [http://data.perseus.org/citations/urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0548.tlg001.perseus-eng1:1.1.7.3 1.7.3]; [[Hesiod]], fr. 10.34\u201345 Most (pp. 54&ndash;55).</ref> He was also said to be the father (with no mothers mentioned) of several [[nymphs]] associated with various springs.<ref>Grimal, s.v. Achelous, p. 4.</ref> These included [[Pirene (mythology)|Pirene]], the nymph of a spring at [[Corinth]],<ref>[[Pausanias (geographer)|Pausanias]], [http://data.perseus.org/citations/urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0525.tlg001.perseus-eng1:2.2.3 2.2.3].</ref> [[Castalia]], the nymph of a spring at [[Delphi]],<ref>[[Panyassis]] [https://www-loebclassics-com.ezproxy.bu.edu/view/panyassis-heraclea/2003/pb_LCL497.193.xml?result=1&rskey=4nH9js fr. 2 West] = [[Pausanias (geographer)|Pausanias]], [http://data.perseus.org/citations/urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0525.tlg001.perseus-eng1:10.8.9 10.8.9].</ref> and Dirce, the nymph of a spring (and the stream that flowed from it) at [[Thebes]], which became associated with the [[Dirce]] who was [[Antiope (mother of Amphion)|Antiope]]'s aunt.<ref>Hard, [https://books.google.com/books?id=r1Y3xZWVlnIC&pg=PA304 p. 304]; [[Euripides]], ''[[Bacchae]]'' [https://www-loebclassics-com.ezproxy.bu.edu/view/euripides-bacchae/2003/pb_LCL495.61.xml?result=3&rskey=k7OCry 519&ndash;520].</ref> Plato has \"the nymphs\" as daughters of Achelous.<ref>[[Plato]], ''[[Phaedrus (dialogue)|Phaedrus]]'' [http://data.perseus.org/citations/urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0059.tlg012.perseus-eng1:263d 263d].</ref> He was also the father (again with no mother metioned) of [[Alcmaeon (mythology)|Alcmeon]]'s second wife [[Callirrhoe (daughter of Achelous)|Callirrhoe]], whose name means \"the lovely spring\".<ref>Hard, [https://books.google.com/books?id=r1Y3xZWVlnIC&pg=PA327 p. 327]; Grimal, s.v. Achelous, p. 4; [[Bibliotheca (Pseudo-Apollodorus)|Apollodorus]], [http://data.perseus.org/citations/urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0548.tlg001.perseus-eng1:1.3.7.5 3.7.5]; [[Pausanias (geographer)|Pausanias]], [http://data.perseus.org/citations/urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0525.tlg001.perseus-eng1:8.24.9 8.24.9].</ref>\n\n==Mythology==\n===Heracles and Deianeira===\nAchelous was a suitor for [[Deianeira]], daughter of [[Oeneus]], the king of [[Calydon]]; he transformed himself into a bull and fought Heracles for the right to marry Deianeira, but was defeated, and Heracles married Deianeira.<ref>Gantz, pp. 28&ndash;29, 41&ndash;42, 431&ndash;433; Hard, pp. [https://books.google.com/books?id=r1Y3xZWVlnIC&pg=PA41 41], [https://books.google.com/books?id=r1Y3xZWVlnIC&pg=PA279 279&ndash;280]; [[Sophocles]], ''[[Women of Trachis]]'' [http://data.perseus.org/citations/urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0011.tlg001.perseus-eng1:1-48 9&ndash;21]; [[Ovid]], ''[[Metamorphoses]]'' [https://www-loebclassics-com.ezproxy.bu.edu/view/ovid-metamorphoses/1916/pb_LCL043.3.xml 9.1&ndash;100]; [[Bibliotheca (Pseudo-Apollodorus)|Apollodorus]], [http://data.perseus.org/citations/urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0548.tlg001.perseus-eng1:1.8.1 1.8.1], [http://data.perseus.org/citations/urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0548.tlg001.perseus-eng1:2.7.5 2.7.5].</ref> The story of Achelous battle with Heracles, as a bull, for Deianeira, was apparently told as early as the 7th century BC, in a lost poem by the Greek poet [[Archilochus]], while according to a summary of a lost poem by the early 5th-century BC Greek poet [[Pindar]], during the battle, Heracles broke off one of Achelous's bull-horns, and the river-god was able to get his horn back by trading it for a horn from [[Amalthea (mythology)|Amalthea]].<ref>Gantz, pp. 28, 41&ndash;42, 432; Hard, [https://books.google.com/books?id=r1Y3xZWVlnIC&pg=PA280 p. 280]; Jebb, [http://www.perseus.tufts.edu/hopper/text?doc=Perseus%3Atext%3A1999.04.0027%3Atext%3Dintro%3Asection%3D5 Introduction 5]; [[Archilochus]], [https://www-loebclassics-com.ezproxy.bu.edu/view/archilochus-fragments/1999/pb_LCL259.267.xml?rskey=5pZe9f&result=1 fr. 286 West] [= [[Dio Chrysostom]], [https://penelope.uchicago.edu/Thayer/E/Roman/Texts/Dio_Chrysostom/Discourses/60*.html 60.1]], [https://www-loebclassics-com.ezproxy.bu.edu/view/archilochus-fragments/1999/pb_LCL259.267.xml?rskey=5pZe9f&result=1 fr. 287 West] [= Scholiast on Homer, ''Iliad'' 21.237]. Compare with [[Bibliotheca (Pseudo-Apollodorus)|Apollodorus]], [http://data.perseus.org/citations/urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0548.tlg001.perseus-eng1:2.7.5 2.7.5], which says that the horn of Amalthea which Acelous traded for his broken-off horn, was also a bull's horn which, \"according to Pherecydes, had the power of supplying meat or drink in abundance, whatever one might wish\". According to Hard, [https://books.google.com/books?id=r1Y3xZWVlnIC&pg=PA280 p. 280], Apollodorus making Amalthea's horn of plenty a bull's horn was \"evidently a misapprehension\" arising from the fact that it was traded for the bull-horn of Achelous.</ref>\n\n[[Sophocles]], in his play ''[[Women of Trachis]]'' (c. 450&ndash;425 BC), has Deianeira tell her story, how Achelous wooed her in the shape of a bull, a snake, and a half-man/half-bull:<ref>Gantz, p. 432.</ref>\n:For my suitor was a river-god, Achelous, who in three shapes was always asking me from my father\u2014coming now as a bull in visible form, now as a serpent, sheeny and coiled, now ox-faced with human trunk, while from his thick-shaded beard wellheads of fountain-water sprayed. In the expectation that such a suitor would get me, I was always praying in my misery that I might die, before I should ever approach that marriage-bed. But at last, to my joy, the glorious son of Zeus and Alcmena came and closed with him in combat and delivered me.<ref>[[Sophocles]], ''[[Women of Trachis]]'' [http://data.perseus.org/citations/urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0011.tlg001.perseus-eng1:1-48 9&ndash;21]; compare with the Chorus's description of the fight at [http://data.perseus.org/citations/urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0011.tlg001.perseus-eng1:497-506 497&ndash;525].</ref>\n\nIn later accounts, Achelous does not get his horn back, as he did in Pindar's poem. [[Ovid]], in his poem ''[[Metamorphoses]]'' (8 AD), has Achelous tell the story.<ref>Gantz, p. 433; [[Ovid]], ''[[Metamorphoses]]'' [https://www-loebclassics-com.ezproxy.bu.edu/view/ovid-metamorphoses/1916/pb_LCL043.3.xml 9.1&ndash;100]; compare with [[Ovid]], ''[[Amores (Ovid)|Amores]]'' [http://data.perseus.org/citations/urn:cts:latinLit:phi0959.phi001.perseus-eng2:3.6 3.6.35&ndash;36].</ref> In this version, Achelous fights Heracles, and loses three times: first in his normal (human?) shape, then as a snake, and finally as a bull. Heracles tore off one of Achelous's bull-horns, and the [[Naiads]] filled the horn with fruit and flowers, transforming it into the \"Horn of Plenty\" ([[cornucopia]]).<ref>Gantz, p. 42; [[Ovid]], ''[[Metamorphoses]]'' [https://www-loebclassics-com.ezproxy.bu.edu/view/ovid-metamorphoses/1916/pb_LCL043.3.xml 9.85&ndash;88].</ref> According to the ''[[Fabulae]]'' (before 207 AD), by the Latin mythographer [[Hyginus]], Heracles gave the broken-off horn to \"the Hesperides (or Nymphs)\", and it was \"these goddesses\" who \"filled the horn with fruit and called it \"Cornucopia\".<ref>[[Hyginus]], ''[[Fabulae]]'' 31.</ref> According to [[Strabo]], in some versions of the story Heracles gave  Achelous's horn to Deianeira's father [[Oeneus]] as a wedding gift.<ref>Jebb, [http://www.perseus.tufts.edu/hopper/text?doc=Perseus%3Atext%3A1999.04.0027%3Atext%3Dcomm%3Acommline%3D518 note on line 518]; [[Strabo]], [http://data.perseus.org/citations/urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0099.tlg001.perseus-eng1:10.2.19 10.2.19].</ref>  While several sources make Achelous the father, by various mothers, of the [[Siren (mythology)|Siren]]s (see above), according to the 4th-century AD Greek teacher of rhetoric [[Libanius]], they were born from the blood Achelous shed when Heracles broke off his horn.<ref>Grimal, s.v. Sirens p. 421; Ker\u00e9nyi  1959, p. 199; Ker\u00e9nyi 1951, p. 56; [[Libanius]], ''[[Progymnasmata]],'' Narration 1: \"On Deianira\" (Gibson,   [https://books.google.com/books?id=kRi-If9IAOYC&pg=PA10 pp. 10&ndash;11]),  Narration 31: \"On Deianira\" (Gibson,   [https://books.google.com/books?id=kRi-If9IAOYC&pg=PA32 pp. 32&ndash;33]). Compare with the birth of the [[Erinyes]] (Furies), [[Giants (Greek mythology)|Giants]], and the [[Meliae]], born the from the blood shed when [[Uranus]] was castrated by his son, the [[Titans (mythology)|Titan]] [[Cronus]].</ref>\n\nBoth [[Diodorus Siculus]] and [[Strabo]] provide rationalized accounts of the story.<ref>[[James George Frazer|Frazer]], note 2 to [[Bibliotheca (Pseudo-Apollodorus)|Apollodorus]] [http://data.perseus.org/citations/urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0548.tlg001.perseus-eng1:2.7.5 2.7.5]; Smith, [http://www.perseus.tufts.edu/hopper/text?doc=Perseus%3Atext%3A1999.04.0104%3Aalphabetic+letter%3DA%3Aentry+group%3D3%3Aentry%3Dachelous-bio-1 s.v. Achelous]; [[Diodorus Siculus]], [https://penelope.uchicago.edu/Thayer/E/Roman/Texts/Diodorus_Siculus/4B*.html#35 4.35.3&ndash;4]; [[Strabo]], [http://data.perseus.org/citations/urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0099.tlg001.perseus-eng1:10.2.19 10.2.19].</ref> According to Diodorus, Heracles diverted the Achelous River, while according to Strabo, to please his father-in-law Oeneus, Heracles confined the river by means of \"embankments and channels\". In this way, Heracles defeated the raging river, and in so doing created a large amount of new arable land and \"certain poets, as we are told, have made this deed into a myth\" (Diodorus).  By both accounts, this new bountiful land came to be known as Amaltheia's horn of plenty.\n\n===Other stories===\nAchelous played a role in the story of the [[Thebes, Greece|Theban]] hero [[Alcmaeon (mythology)|Alcmaeon]], who had killed his mother [[Eriphyle]] because of her treachery against his father [[Amphiaraus]], and needed to be religiously purified.<ref>Hard, [https://books.google.com/books?id=r1Y3xZWVlnIC&pg=PA327 p. 327]; Grimal, s.v. Alcmaeon, p. 31.</ref> According to Apollodorus, Alcmaeon was first purified by [[Phegeus]] the king of [[Psophis]], but nevertheless the land of Psophis became barren because of the cursed Alcmaeon's presence. As Thucydides tells the story, the oracle of Apollo told Alcmaeon that he needed to find a land to live in that did not yet exist at the time of his mother's death. After long travels, Alcmaeon finally came to the springs of the Achelous River, where he was purified by the river-god, and received Achelous's daughter Callirrhoe as his wife, and at the mouth of the river he discovered a land newly made by deposits of river silt, where he could make his home free of his curse.<ref>[[Bibliotheca (Pseudo-Apollodorus)|Apollodorus]], [http://data.perseus.org/citations/urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0548.tlg001.perseus-eng1:3.7.5 3.7.5]; [[Thucydides]], [http://data.perseus.org/citations/urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0003.tlg001.perseus-eng2:2.102 2.102.2&ndash;6]. Compare with [[Pausanias (geographer)|Pausanias]], [http://data.perseus.org/citations/urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0525.tlg001.perseus-eng1:8.24.8 8.24.8&ndash;9].</ref> Later, according to Apollodorus, Achelous commanded Alcmaeon to dedicate the [[Necklace of Harmonia|necklace]] and robe&mdash;the cause of his mother's treachery&mdash; at [[Delphi]], which he did.<ref>[[Bibliotheca (Pseudo-Apollodorus)|Apollodorus]], [http://data.perseus.org/citations/urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0548.tlg001.perseus-eng1:3.7.7 3.7.7].</ref>\n\n[[File:Metropolitan Rubens Achelous.jpg|thumb|upright=1.5|''The Banquet of Achelous'', by [[Rubens]], c. 1615]]\n\nOvid, in his ''Metamorphoses'', has the river-god involved in two transformation stories concerning the creation of islands near the mouth of the Achelous River.<ref>Hard, [https://books.google.com/books?id=r1Y3xZWVlnIC&pg=PA42 p. 42]; Tripp,  s.v. Achelo\u00fcs, p. 5.</ref> According to Ovid, the [[Echinades Islands]] were once five local nymphs.<ref>[[Ovid]], ''[[Metamorphoses]]'' [https://www-loebclassics-com.ezproxy.bu.edu/view/ovid-metamorphoses/1916/pb_LCL042.447.xml 8.574&ndash;589].</ref> One day, the nymphs were offering sacrifices to the gods on the banks of the Achelous, but they forgot to include Achelous himself. The river-god became so angry, he overflowed his banks with a raging flood, sweeping the nymphs away into the sea. As Achelous tells the story:\n:\"I tore forests from forests, fields from fields; and with the place they stood on, I swept the nymphs away, who at last remembered me then, into the sea. There my flood and the sea, united, cleft the undivided ground into as many parts as now you see the Echinades yonder amid the waves.\"<ref>[[Ovid]], ''[[Metamorphoses]]'' [https://www-loebclassics-com.ezproxy.bu.edu/view/ovid-metamorphoses/1916/pb_LCL042.447.xml 8.583&ndash;589].</ref>\n\nAchelous goes on to describe the creation of another island: \"far away beyond the others is one island that I love: the sailors call it [[Perimele]].\"<ref>[[Ovid]], ''[[Metamorphoses]]'' [https://www-loebclassics-com.ezproxy.bu.edu/view/ovid-metamorphoses/1916/pb_LCL042.447.xml 8.590&ndash;591].</ref> She was the daughter of [[Hippodamas]], whose virginity Achelous took from her. Her enraged father threw her off a high cliff into the sea. But Achelous prayed to [[Posiedon]] to save her, and in answer Poseidon transformed the girl into an island.<ref>[[Ovid]], ''[[Metamorphoses]]'' [https://www-loebclassics-com.ezproxy.bu.edu/view/ovid-metamorphoses/1916/pb_LCL042.449.xml 8.592&ndash;610].</ref>\n\n==Iconography==\n[[Image:Annibale Fontana - Plaque with Hercules and Achelous - Walters 4171.jpg|thumb|The fight of Heracles and the river-god Achelous is depicted in this plaque by [[Annibale Fontana]].<ref>{{cite web |publisher= [[The Walters Art Museum]] |url= http://art.thewalters.org/detail/21338 |title= Plaque with Hercules and Achelous }}</ref>]]\n\nThe contest of Achelous with Heracles was represented on the throne of [[Amyclae]],<ref>[[Pausanias (geographer)|Pausanias]], [http://data.perseus.org/citations/urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0525.tlg001.perseus-eng1:3.18.16 3.18.16].</ref> and in the treasury of the [[Megara]]ns at [[Olympia, Greece|Olympia]] there was a statue of him made by [[Dontas]] of cedarwood and gold.<ref>[[Pausanias (geographer)|Pausanias]], [http://data.perseus.org/citations/urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0525.tlg001.perseus-eng1:6.19.12 6.19.12].</ref> Achelous was sometimes depicted as a gray-haired old man or a vigorous bearded man in his prime, with a horned head and a serpent-like body. On several coins of [[Acarnania]] the god is represented as a bull with the head of an old man.<ref>Comp. Philostr. ''Imag.'' n. 4.</ref> The most common depiction of Achelous in Archaic and Classical times was this man-faced bull.<ref>Molinari and Sisci, pp. 91&ndash;96.</ref> Often a city would feature a man-faced bull on its coinage to represent a local variant of Achelous, such as Achelous Gelas of [[Gela]], Sicily, or Achelous Sebethos of [[Naples|Neapolis]], Campania.<ref>Molinari and Sisci, pp. 97ff.</ref>\n\n==Cult==\nFrom at least as early as [[Homer]],<ref>[[Homer]], ''[[Iliad]]'' [http://data.perseus.org/citations/urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.perseus-eng1:21.161-21.199 194].</ref> Achelous was apparently considered to be an important divinity throughout Greece.<ref>Fowler, p. 12; [[Richard Claverhouse Jebb|Jebb]], [http://www.perseus.tufts.edu/hopper/text?doc=Perseus%3Atext%3A1999.04.0027%3Atext%3Dcomm%3Acommline%3D9 note on line 9]; Smith, [http://www.perseus.tufts.edu/hopper/text?doc=Perseus%3Atext%3A1999.04.0104%3Aalphabetic+letter%3DA%3Aentry+group%3D3%3Aentry%3Dachelous-bio-1 s.v. Achelous].</ref> According to the early 4th-century BC Greek historian [[Ephorus]], the oracle at [[Dodona]] usually added to his pronouncements the command to offer sacrifices to Achelous, and that, while people would offer sacrifices to their local river, only the Achelous river was honoured everywhere, with Achelous's name often being invoked in oaths, prayers and sacrifices, \"all the things that concern the gods.\"<ref>[[Ephorus]] ''[[FGrHist]]'' 70 20a = [[Macrobius]], ''[[Saturnalia (Macrobius)|Saturnalia]]'' [https://www-loebclassics-com.ezproxy.bu.edu/view/macrobius-saturnalia/2011/pb_LCL511.423.xml 5.18.6&ndash;8].</ref>\n\n[[Plato]] has [[Socrates]], walking in the countryside, come across a \"sacred place of some nymphs and of Achelous, judging by the figurines and statues\".<ref>[[Plato]], ''[[Phaedrus (dialogue)|Phaedrus]]'' [http://data.perseus.org/citations/urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0059.tlg012.perseus-eng1:230b 230b].</ref> The 2nd-century geographer [[Pausanias (geographer)|Pausanias]], mentions a part of the altar at the [[Amphiareion of Oropos]] dedicated to \"the nymphs and to Pan, and to the rivers Achelous and Cephisus\",<ref>[[Pausanias (geographer)|Pausanias]], [http://data.perseus.org/citations/urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0525.tlg001.perseus-eng1:1.34 1.34.3].</ref> as well as an altar to Achelous near [[Megara]],<ref>[[Pausanias (geographer)|Pausanias]], [http://data.perseus.org/citations/urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0525.tlg001.perseus-eng1:1.41.2 1.41.2].</ref> and the [[Megarian Treasury (Olympia)|Megarian Treasury]] at [[Olympia, Greece|Olympia]], which contained dedications in the form of \"small cedar-wood figures inlaid with gold, representing the fight of Heracles with Achelous,\" which, besides Achelous, included [[Zeus]], [[Deianeira]], [[Heracles]], and [[Ares]] aiding Achelous.<ref>[[Pausanias (geographer)|Pausanias]], [http://data.perseus.org/citations/urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0525.tlg001.perseus-eng1:6.19.12 6.19.12].</ref>\n\n==Origin==\n\nCalling Achelous \"king\", [[Homer]] mentions Achelous (along with Oceanus) as a mighty river, using him as a measure of the strength of the even mightier Zeus:<ref>Gantz, p. 28.</ref>\n:With [Zeus] doth not even king Achelous vie, nor the great might of deep-flowing Ocean, from whom all rivers flow and every sea, and all the springs and deep wells;<ref>[[Homer]], ''[[Iliad]]'' [http://data.perseus.org/citations/urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.perseus-eng1:21.161-21.199 21.194&ndash;195]; compare [[Pausanias (geographer)|Pausanias]], [http://data.perseus.org/citations/urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0525.tlg001.perseus-eng1:8.38.10 8.38.10].</ref>\nSome ancient scholars thought that the line: \"nor the great might of deep-flowing Ocean\", was spurious, thus making Achelous, instead of Oceanus, the source of all other waters, and some ancient verses apparently equated Achelous with Oceanus.<ref>Fowler 2013, p. 12; Andolfi, fr. 1.</ref> His name was often used to mean \"water\".<ref>Fowler 2013, p. 12; Molinari and Sisci, p. 60; Andolfi, fr. 1; West 1983, p. 92 n. 39; [[Macrobius]], ''[[Saturnalia (Macrobius)|Saturnalia]]'' [https://www-loebclassics-com.ezproxy.bu.edu/view/macrobius-saturnalia/2011/pb_LCL511.421.xml 5.18.1&ndash;12]; [[Maurus Servius Honoratus|Servius]], On Virgil's ''Georgics'' [http://www.perseus.tufts.edu/hopper/text?doc=Perseus%3Atext%3A2007.01.0092%3Abook%3D1%3Acommline%3D8 1.8] (which ascribes the usage to [[Orpheus]], see Orphic [https://archive.org/stream/orphicorumfragme00orphuoft#page/336/mode/2up fr. 344 Kern]). See for example: [[Sophocles]] fr. 5 Lloyd-Jones; [[Euripides]], ''[[Bacchae]]'' [https://www-loebclassics-com.ezproxy.bu.edu/view/euripides-bacchae/2003/pb_LCL495.71.xml?result=3&rskey=k7OCry 625], ''Hypsipyle'', [https://www-loebclassics-com.ezproxy.bu.edu/view/euripides-dramatic_fragments/2008/pb_LCL506.283.xml fr. 753] [= [[Macrobius]], ''[[Saturnalia (Macrobius)|Saturnalia]]'' [https://www-loebclassics-com.ezproxy.bu.edu/view/macrobius-saturnalia/2011/pb_LCL511.427.xml 5.18.12]]; [[Aristophanes]] [https://www-loebclassics-com.ezproxy.bu.edu/view/aristophanes-attributed_fragments/2008/pb_LCL502.285.xml fr. 365 Henderson] = fr. 365 ''PCG'' = [[Macrobius]], ''[[Saturnalia (Macrobius)|Saturnalia]]'' [https://www-loebclassics-com.ezproxy.bu.edu/view/macrobius-saturnalia/2011/pb_LCL511.423.xml 5.18.5]. As an explanation for this \"puzzle\", [[Ephorus]] (''[[FGrHist]]'' 70 20a = [[Macrobius]], ''[[Saturnalia (Macrobius)|Saturnalia]]'' [https://www-loebclassics-com.ezproxy.bu.edu/view/macrobius-saturnalia/2011/pb_LCL511.423.xml 5.18.6&ndash;8]) says that the oracle at [[Dodona]], in his pronouncements, usually commanded a sacrifice to Achelous, and he speculates that, because of this, it came to be thought that by \"Achelous\" the oracle meant, not the river but \"water\" in general, see Andolfi, fr. 1.</ref> These and other evidence from ancient sources have suggested the possibility to modern scholars that Achelous may have predated Oceanus as the original Greek water-god.<ref>Fowler 2013, p. 12.</ref>\n\n[[File:Bronze coin from Oiniadai.jpg|right|thumb|[[Bronze]] coin struck in [[Oiniadai]], c. 215 BC, depicting the [[river-god]] Achelous as man-faced [[bull]] on reverse.]]\n\nA recent study has tried to show that both the form and substance of Achelous, as a god of water primarily depicted as a man-faced bull, have roots in [[Old Europe (archaeology)|Old Europe]] in the [[Bronze Age]]. After the disappearance of many Old European cultures, the traditions traveled to the Near East at the beginning of 4th millennium BC ([[Ubaid period]]),<ref>Molinari and Sisci, pp. 1&ndash;6.</ref> and finally migrated to Greece, Italy, Sicily, and Sardinia with itinerant sea-folk during the Late Bronze Age through the [[Orientalizing period]].<ref>Molinari and Sisci, pp. 22&ndash;30.</ref> Although no single cult of Achelous persisted throughout all of these generations, the iconography and general ''mythos'' easily spread from one culture to another, and all examples of man-faced bulls are found around the area of the Mediterraneanan, suggesting some intercultural continuity.<ref>Molinari and Sisci, pp. 97ff.</ref> The leading exponents into the Greek and Etruscan worlds were seer-healers and mercenaries during the [[Iron Age]], and Achelous as a man-faced bull becomes an emblem employed by mercenaries in the Greek world for centuries.<ref>Molinari and Sisci, pp. 22&ndash;30.</ref> These earlier figures probably adapted the mythological and iconographic traditions of Asall\u00fahi (also Asarl\u00fahi or [[Asaruludu]]),<ref>Molinari and Sisci, p. 14.</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://oracc.museum.upenn.edu/amgg/listofdeities/asalluhi/|title=Asalluhi (god)|last=Heffron|first=Ya\u01e7mur|last2=Brisch|first2=Nicole|date=2016|website=Ancient Mesopotamian Gods and Goddesses|publisher=University of Pennsylvania|access-date=20 October 2016}}</ref> the \"princely bison\" of Near Eastern traditions that \"rises to the surface of the earth in springs and marshes, ultimately flowing as rivers.\"<ref>{{Cite book|title=Milking the Udder of Heaven: A Note on Mesopotamian and Indo-Iranian Religious Imagery|last=Whittaker|first=Gordon|work=From Daena to Din. Religion, Kultur und Sprache in der iranischen Welt: Festschrift fuer Philip Kreyenbroek zum 60. Geburstag|publisher=Harrassowitz Verlag|year=2009|isbn=|location=Wiesbaden|pages=131|quote=|via=}}</ref>\n\n==The Achelous River==\nHomer claims that the Achelous River was located in Lydia, near Mount Sipylos.<ref>{{Cite book|title=Iliad|last=Homer|first=|publisher=|year=|isbn=|location=|pages=24.616|quote=|via=}}</ref> There were at least six different rivers with the name Achelous in ancient times,<ref>Molinari and Sisci, p. 61.</ref> all of which indicate that Achelous was originally not a single river, but a god of all water.\n\n[[Maurus Servius Honoratus|Servius]] gives a story of the origin of the river. He says that one day Achelous, who was said to be the son of Earth, lost his daughters the Sirens, and in his grief he called upon his mother, who received him into her bosom, and on that spot, Earth caused a river, bearing his name, to gush forth.<ref>Smith, [http://www.perseus.tufts.edu/hopper/text?doc=Perseus%3Atext%3A1999.04.0104%3Aalphabetic+letter%3DA%3Aentry+group%3D3%3Aentry%3Dachelous-bio-1 s.v. Achelous]; [[Maurus Servius Honoratus|Servius]], ''ad Virg. Georg.'' i. 9.</ref>\n\n[[Pseudo-Plutarch]] gives a different story for how the river acquired its name. He says it was formerly called Thestius, after a son of [[Mars]] and [[Pisidice]], who jumped into the river after discovering he had killed his son Calydon by mistake. In a similar fashion the river acquired the name Achelous, after a son of Oceanus and the nymph Nais, who jumped into the river after he discovered he had slept with his daughter Cletoria by mistake.<ref>Smith, [http://www.perseus.tufts.edu/hopper/text?doc=Perseus%3Atext%3A1999.04.0104%3Aalphabetic+letter%3DA%3Aentry+group%3D3%3Aentry%3Dachelous-bio-1 s.v. Achelous]; [[Pseudo-Plutarch]], ''De fluviis'' [http://data.perseus.org/citations/urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0094.tlg001.perseus-eng1:22 22]. See also [[Stephanus of Byzantium]].</ref>\n\nStrabo attributed various legends concerning Achelous, to features of the Achelous River itself. He says that, like other rivers, Achelous was called \"like a bull\", because of the rivers roaring waters, and its meanders (which he says were called horns). Likewise Achelous was called \"like a serpent\" because of the river's great length and many serpentine turnings.<ref>Smith, [http://www.perseus.tufts.edu/hopper/text?doc=Perseus%3Atext%3A1999.04.0104%3Aalphabetic+letter%3DA%3Aentry+group%3D3%3Aentry%3Dachelous-bio-1 s.v. Achelous]; [[Strabo]], [http://data.perseus.org/citations/urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0099.tlg001.perseus-eng1:10.2.19 10.2.19]. Compare with [[Diodorus Siculus]], [https://penelope.uchicago.edu/Thayer/E/Roman/Texts/Diodorus_Siculus/4B*.html#35 4.35.3&ndash;4].</ref>\n\n==In the ''Metamorphoses''==\n\n[[Ovid]] in his ''Metamorphoses'' provided a descriptive interlude when [[Theseus]] is the guest of Achelous, waiting for the river's raging flood to subside: \"He entered the dark building, made of spongy pumice, and rough tuff. The floor was moist with soft moss, and the ceiling banded with freshwater mussel and oyster shells.\"<ref>[[Ovid]], ''[[Metamorphoses]]'' VIII, 547ff.</ref>\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n==References==\n* Andolfi, Ilaria, ''Acusilaus of Argos\u2019 Rhapsody in Prose: Introduction, Text, and Commentary'', Walter de Gruyter GmbH & Co KG, 2019. {{ISBN|978-3-11-061695-8}}.\n* Andrews, Tamra. ''A Dictionary of Nature Myths'', 1998. {{ISBN|0-19-513677-2}}.\n* [[Bibliotheca (Pseudo-Apollodorus)|Apollodorus]], ''Apollodorus, The Library, with an English Translation by Sir James George Frazer, F.B.A., F.R.S. in 2 Volumes.'' Cambridge, Massachusetts, [[Harvard University Press]]; London, William Heinemann Ltd. 1921. [http://www.perseus.tufts.edu/hopper/text?doc=urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0548.tlg001.perseus-eng1 Online version at the Perseus Digital Library].\n* [[Apollonius of Rhodes]], ''Apollonius Rhodius: the Argonautica'', translated by Robert Cooper Seaton, W. Heinemann, 1912. [http://www.archive.org/stream/argonautica00apoluoft#page/n5/mode/2up Internet Archive].\n* [[Aristophanes]], ''Fragments'', edited and translated by Jeffrey Henderson, [[Loeb Classical Library]] No. 502, Cambridge, Massachusetts, [[Harvard University Press]], 2007. [https://www-loebclassics-com.ezproxy.bu.edu/view/LCL502/2008/volume.xml Online version at Harvard University Press]. {{ISBN|978-0-674-99615-1}}.\n* [[Aristotle]], ''[[Metaphysics]]'' in  ''Aristotle 