{"title_page": "Pirates of the Caribbean (film series)", "text_new": "{{pp-pc1|small=yes}}\n{{short description|Series of fantasy adventure films}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name           = Pirates of the Caribbean\n| image          = Pirates of the Caribbean logo.svg\n| director       = [[Gore Verbinski]] (1\u20133) <br />[[Rob Marshall]] (4) <br />[[Espen Sandberg]] (5) <br />[[Joachim R\u00f8nning]] (5-6)\n| producer       = [[Jerry Bruckheimer]]\n| screenplay     = [[Ted Elliott (screenwriter)|Ted Elliott]] <br />[[Terry Rossio]] (1\u20134) <br />[[Jeff Nathanson]] (5) <br />[[Craig Mazin]] (6)\n| story          = Ted Elliott <br />Terry Rossio (1\u20135) <br />Jeff Nathanson (5) <br />[[Stuart Beattie]] (1) <br />[[Jay Wolpert]] (1)\n| based on       = [[Pirates of the Caribbean (attraction)|Pirates of the Caribbean]] <br />by [[Walt Disney]]<br />''[[On Stranger Tides]]'' <br />by [[Tim Powers]] (4)\n| starring       = [[Johnny Depp]] <br />[[Geoffrey Rush]] <br />[[Orlando Bloom]] <br />[[Keira Knightley]] <br />[[Kevin McNally]] <br /> [[Bill Nighy]] <br /> ([[#Cast and crew|See below]])\n| music          = [[Klaus Badelt]] (1) <br />[[Hans Zimmer]] (2\u20134) <br />[[Geoff Zanelli]] (5)\n| studio         = [[Walt Disney Pictures]] <br />Jerry Bruckheimer Films\n| distributor    = [[Walt Disney Studios Motion Pictures]]\n| released       =\n| runtime        = 726 minutes (1\u20135)<!-- Runtime from backs of DVD boxes, if you replace time, update source. -->\n| country        = United States<!--Please provide a reliable source for any country other than the US.-->\n| language       = English\n| budget         = '''Total (5 films):''' <br />$1.274&nbsp;billion\n| gross          = '''Total (5 films):''' <br />$4.524 billion\n}}\n\n'''''Pirates of the Caribbean''''' is a series of [[Fantasy film|fantasy]] [[swashbuckler film]]s produced by [[Jerry Bruckheimer]] and loosely based on [[Walt Disney]]'s [[Pirates of the Caribbean (attraction)|eponymous theme park attraction]].\n\nDirectors of the series include [[Gore Verbinski]] (films 1\u20133), [[Rob Marshall]]&nbsp;(4), [[Joachim R\u00f8nning]], and [[Espen Sandberg]] (5). The series is primarily written by [[Ted Elliott (screenwriter)|Ted Elliott]] and [[Terry Rossio]] (1\u20134); other writers include [[Stuart Beattie]] (1), [[Jay Wolpert]] (1), [[Jeff Nathanson]] (5), [[Craig Mazin]] (6). The stories follow the adventures of [[Jack Sparrow|Captain Jack Sparrow]] ([[Johnny Depp]]), [[Will Turner]] ([[Orlando Bloom]]) and [[Elizabeth Swann]] ([[Keira Knightley]]). Characters such as [[Hector Barbossa]] ([[Geoffrey Rush]]) and [[Joshamee Gibbs]] ([[Kevin McNally]]) follow Jack, Will and Elizabeth in the course of the films. The fourth film features [[List of Pirates of the Caribbean characters#Blackbeard|Blackbeard]] ([[Ian McShane]]) and [[List of Pirates of the Caribbean characters#Angelica|Angelica]] ([[Pen\u00e9lope Cruz]]), while the fifth film features [[List of Pirates of the Caribbean characters#Armando Salazar|Armando Salazar]] ([[Javier Bardem]]), [[List of Pirates of the Caribbean characters#Henry Turner|Henry Turner]] ([[Brenton Thwaites]]) and [[List of Pirates of the Caribbean characters#Carina Barbossa|Carina Smyth]] ([[Kaya Scodelario]]). The films take place in a fictionalized historical setting; a world ruled by the [[British Empire]], the East India Trading Company (based on the real [[East India Company|East India Trading Company]]) and the [[Spanish Empire]], with pirates representing freedom from the ruling powers.\n\nThe film series started in 2003 with ''[[Pirates of the Caribbean: The Curse of the Black Pearl]]'', which received positive reviews from critics and grossed [[United States dollar|US$]]654 million worldwide.<ref name=\"List By Box Office Sales\">{{cite web|url=http://www.johnnydeppmovieslist.org/#ByWWSales |title=Johnny Depp Movies List by Box Office Sales |website=JohnnyDeppMoviesList.org |accessdate=2015-01-22}}</ref> After the first film's success, [[Walt Disney Pictures]] revealed that a film series was in the works. The franchise's second film, subtitled ''[[Pirates of the Caribbean: Dead Man's Chest|Dead Man's Chest]]'', was released three years later in 2006; the sequel proved successful, breaking financial records worldwide the day of its premiere. ''Dead Man's Chest'' ended up being the number one film of the year upon earning almost $1.1 billion at the worldwide box office. The third film in the series, subtitled ''[[Pirates of the Caribbean: At World's End|At World's End]]'', followed in 2007 earning $960 million, and Disney released a fourth film, subtitled ''[[Pirates of the Caribbean: On Stranger Tides|On Stranger Tides]]'', in 2011 in conventional 2D, [[Digital 3-D]] and [[IMAX 3D]]. ''On Stranger Tides'' succeeded in also grossing more than $1 billion,<ref name=\"List By Box Office Sales\" /> becoming the second film in the franchise and only the eighth film in history to achieve this.\n\nThe franchise has grossed over $4.5 billion worldwide;<ref name=\"List By Box Office Sales\" /> it is the [[List of highest-grossing franchises and film series|14th-highest-grossing film series]] of all time, and it was the first franchise where more than one film grossed $1 billion worldwide.\n\n==Films==\n{| class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders\" style=\"text-align:center\" width=100%\n! scope=\"col\" | Film\n! scope=\"col\" | U.S. release date\n! scope=\"col\" | Director(s)\n! scope=\"col\" | Screenwriter(s)\n! scope=\"col\" | Story by\n! scope=\"col\" | Producer\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" style=\"text-align:left\" | ''[[Pirates of the Caribbean: The Curse of the Black Pearl|The Curse of the Black Pearl]]''\n| style=\"text-align:left\" | {{Start date|2003|07|09}}\n| rowspan=\"3\" | [[Gore Verbinski]]\n| rowspan=\"4\" | [[Ted Elliott (screenwriter)|Ted Elliot]] and [[Terry Rossio]]\n| Ted Elliott and Terry Rossio, [[Stuart Beattie]] and [[Jay Wolpert]]\n| rowspan=\"5\" | [[Jerry Bruckheimer]]\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" style=\"text-align:left\" | ''[[Pirates of the Caribbean: Dead Man's Chest|Dead Man's Chest]]''\n| style=\"text-align:left\" | {{Start date|2006|07|07}}\n| rowspan=\"3\" | Ted Elliott and Terry Rossio\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" style=\"text-align:left\" | ''[[Pirates of the Caribbean: At World's End|At World's End]]''\n| style=\"text-align:left\" | {{Start date|2007|05|25}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" style=\"text-align:left\" | ''[[Pirates of the Caribbean: On Stranger Tides|On Stranger Tides]]''\n| style=\"text-align:left\" | {{Start date|2011|05|20}}\n| [[Rob Marshall]]\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" style=\"text-align:left\" | ''[[Pirates of the Caribbean: Dead Men Tell No Tales|Dead Men Tell No Tales]]''\n| style=\"text-align:left\" | {{Start date|2017|05|26}}\n| [[Joachim R\u00f8nning]]<br />and [[Espen Sandberg]]\n| [[Jeff Nathanson]]\n| Jeff Nathanson and Terry Rossio\n|}\n\n{{multiple image\n  | align =\n  | direction = vertical\n  | width     = 120\n  | image1    = Johnny Depp 2, 2011.jpg\n  | alt1      = Johnny Depp at a film premiere.\n  | caption1  =\n  | image2    = GeoffreyRushTIFFSept2011.jpg\n  | alt2      = Rush at a festival.\n  | caption2  =\n  | image3    = Orlando Bloom Cannes 2013.jpg\n  | alt3      = Bloom at a festival.\n  | caption3  =\n  | image4    = KeiraKnightleyByAndreaRaffin2011 (cropped).jpg\n  | alt4      = Knightley at a festival.\n  | caption4  =\n  | image5    = Kevin_McNally_January_2015.jpg\n  | alt5      = McNally at a festival.\n  | caption5  =\n  | footer    = Top to bottom: Johnny Depp, Geoffrey Rush, Orlando Bloom, Keira Knightley and Kevin McNally, who portrayed the principal characters. Only Depp, Rush and McNally reprised their roles in every film. Bloom and Knightley did not return for the fourth film and had cameo appearances for the fifth film.\n}}\n\n=== ''The Curse of the Black Pearl '' (2003) ===\n{{Main|Pirates of the Caribbean: The Curse of the Black Pearl}}\n\nBlacksmith [[Will Turner]] teams up with eccentric pirate [[Jack Sparrow|Captain Jack Sparrow]] to save Turner's love, [[Elizabeth Swann]], from cursed pirates led by Jack's mutinous former first mate, [[Hector Barbossa]]. Jack wants revenge against Barbossa, who left him stranded on an island before stealing his ship, the ''Black Pearl'', along with 882 pieces of cursed Aztec Gold.\n\n=== ''Dead Man's Chest'' (2006) ===\n{{Main|Pirates of the Caribbean: Dead Man's Chest}}\n\nLord [[Cutler Beckett]] of the [[East India Company|East India Trading Company]] arrests Will and Elizabeth for aiding Captain Jack Sparrow in the previous film. Beckett offers [[clemency]] if Will agrees to search for Jack's compass in a bid to find the [[Dead Man's Chest]]\u2014and inside, the heart of villainous [[Davy Jones (Pirates of the Caribbean)|Davy Jones]]\u2014which would give Beckett control of the seas. However, Jack wants the Chest to escape from an unpaid debt with Jones, who made Jack captain of the ''Black Pearl'' for 13 years in exchange for 100 years of service aboard Jones' ship, the ''Flying Dutchman''.\n\n=== ''At World's End'' (2007) ===\n{{Main|Pirates of the Caribbean: At World's End}}\n\nLord Beckett gains power over Davy Jones and, with the help of the ''Flying Dutchman'', he is now executing his plans to extinguish piracy forever. To stand against the East India Trading Co., Will, Elizabeth, Barbossa, and the crew of the ''Black Pearl'' set out to rescue Captain Jack Sparrow from [[Davy Jones' Locker]]. As one of the Nine Pirate Lords, Jack is needed in order to release an ancient goddess with the power to defeat Beckett's forces.\n\n=== ''On Stranger Tides'' (2011) ===\n{{Main|Pirates of the Caribbean: On Stranger Tides}}\n\nCaptain Jack Sparrow is on a quest to find the fabled [[Fountain of Youth]] and crosses paths with a former lover, Angelica. She forces Jack aboard the ''[[Queen Anne's Revenge]]'', a ship captained by the infamous pirate [[Blackbeard]], Angelica's father. Both are also in search of the Fountain: Angelica to save her father's soul, Blackbeard to escape a prophecy of his demise at the hands of a one-legged man. Joining the hunt is former pirate captain Barbossa, now a privateer in [[George II of Great Britain|King George II]]'s Navy, who is in a race against the Spanish for the Fountain of Youth.\n\n=== ''Dead Men Tell No Tales'' (2017) ===\n{{Main|Pirates of the Caribbean: Dead Men Tell No Tales}}\n\nA group of ghostly Spanish Royal Navy soldiers led by Jack Sparrow's old nemesis, Captain Armando Salazar, escape from the [[Bermuda Triangle|Devil's Triangle]], with the goal of killing every pirate at sea, including him. To survive, Jack seeks out the legendary [[Trident of Poseidon]], a powerful artifact whose owner can control the seas and break curses.<ref name=\"THR\">{{cite web|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/pirates-caribbean-dead-men-tell-774657 |title='Pirates of the Caribbean: Dead Men Tell No Tales' Plot, Casting Announced as Production Begins |author=Rebecca Ford |work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]] |date=2015-02-17 |accessdate=2015-02-18 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150220152443/http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/pirates-caribbean-dead-men-tell-774657 |archive-date=2015-02-20}}</ref>\n\n===Sixth film===\nShortly before the release of ''[[Pirates of the Caribbean: On Stranger Tides|On Stranger Tides]]'', it was reported that Disney was planning to shoot the fifth and the sixth films back-to-back,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://uproxx.com/hitfix/exclusive-disney-will-set-sail-for-pirates-of-the-caribbean-5-6-back-to-back/ |title=EXCLUSIVE: Disney will set sail for 'Pirates of the Caribbean' 5 & 6 back-to-back |date=3 December 2010 |publisher= |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170307204043/http://uproxx.com/hitfix/exclusive-disney-will-set-sail-for-pirates-of-the-caribbean-5-6-back-to-back/ |archive-date=March 7, 2017 }}</ref> although ultimately only the fifth installment was developed. By March 2017, director [[Joachim R\u00f8nning]] stated that ''Dead Men'' was only the beginning of the final adventure, confirming that it would not be the last film of the series.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://movieweb.com/pirates-caribbean-dead-men-tell-no-tales-not-last-movie/ |title=Pirates 5 May Not Be Captain Jack's Final Adventure |date=March 4, 2017 |publisher= |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170307125630/http://movieweb.com/pirates-caribbean-dead-men-tell-no-tales-not-last-movie/ |archive-date=March 7, 2017 }}</ref> In September 2017, producer Jerry Bruckheimer indicated that another ''Pirates of the Caribbean'' is still in development.<ref>{{cite web |date= 4 September 2017 |author=  Dan Zinski |title= Pirates of the Caribbean 6 Isn't Green-Lit Yet |url= https://screenrant.com/pirates-caribbean-5-dead-men-blu-ray-sales/ |website=ScreenRant }}</ref>\nIn October of the same year, [[Kaya Scodelario]] stated that she is contractually signed to return for a sixth film.<ref>{{cite web |author1=Alex Leadbeater |title=EXCLUSIVE: Kaya Scodelario Contracted To Return for Pirates of the Caribbean 6 |url=https://screenrant.com/pirates-caribbean-6-kaya-scodelario-return/ |website=ScreenRant |date=2 October 2017}}</ref> Shortly after, it was confirmed that R\u00f8nning will direct the film.<ref>https://twitter.com/ComicFade/status/915333922883432448</ref>\n\n=== Short film ===\n==== ''Tales of the Code: Wedlocked'' (2011) ====\nWenches Scarlett (Lauren Maher) and Giselle ([[Vanessa Branch]]) fix each other up for their wedding, in which they would each marry their groom. Upon realizing that both their grooms were the same man\u2014Jack Sparrow\u2014the two wenches find themselves in an auction led by the Auctioneer. The short film serves as a prequel to ''The Curse of the Black Pearl'', explaining just why Jack Sparrow's boat, ''the Jolly Mon'', was seen sinking at the beginning of the whole story, and explaining why wenches Scarlett and Giselle were so upset with him, and it also implies how Cotton lost his tongue. The plot took inspiration from the \"Auction scene\" from the original Disney park attraction.\n\nThe short was directed by [[James Ward Byrkit]],<ref name=\"Wedlocked on Jim Byrkit's official website\">{{cite web|author=Jim Byrkit |title=Wedlocked on Jim Byrkit's portfolio |url=http://jimbyrkit.com/archives/category/portfolio/wedlocked/ |accessdate=2014-07-24 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140717050635/http://jimbyrkit.com/archives/category/portfolio/wedlocked |archivedate=2014-07-17 }}</ref> and was only included as a special feature in the US 15-disc 3D Blu-ray/2D Blu-ray/DVD + Digital Copy box set that includes films 1\u20134; and in the similar UK five-disc set.\n\nByrkit conceived the idea for the project while on sets Rick Heinrichs designed for ''[[Pirates of the Caribbean: Dead Man's Chest]]'' (2006) and ''[[Pirates of the Caribbean: At World's End]]'' (2007). As the pirate cove sets from the feature films\u2014where the short film takes place\u2014were set to be demolished, the short project was prepped in a matter of days and shot over three days. Byrkit based the short film on the Pirate Code Book as it was a device that could tie into other stories later.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/blogs/comic-riffs/post/as-a-creative-renaissance-man-writer-director-james-ward-byrkit-brings-rango-and-pirates-film-to-your-screen/2011/05/26/gIQAhPlKGI_blog.html|title=As a creative renaissance man, writer-director James Ward Byrkit brings 'RANGO' and 'PIRATES' film to your screen|last=Cavna|first=Michael|date=2011-07-15|website=Washington Post|language=en-US|access-date=2018-04-15}}</ref>\n\n==Cast and crew==\n===Cast===\n{{Main|List of Pirates of the Caribbean characters|List of Pirates of the Caribbean cast members}}\n\n===Additional crew===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"  style=\"text-align:center; width:99%;\"\n|-\n! rowspan=\"2\" style=\"width:16.66%;\" | Occupation\n! colspan=5\" style=\"text-align:center;\" | Film\n|-\n! style=\"text-align:center; | ''[[Pirates of the Caribbean: The Curse of the Black Pearl|{{small|Pirates of the Caribbean:}} <br />The Curse of the Black Pearl]]''\n! style=\"text-align:center; | ''[[Pirates of the Caribbean: Dead Man's Chest|{{small|Pirates of the Caribbean:}} <br />Dead Man's Chest]]''\n! style=\"text-align:center; | ''[[Pirates of the Caribbean: At World's End|{{small|Pirates of the Caribbean:}} <br />At World's End]]''\n! style=\"text-align:center; | ''[[Pirates of the Caribbean: On Stranger Tides|{{small|Pirates of the Caribbean:}} <br />On Stranger Tides]]''\n! style=\"text-align:center; | ''[[Pirates of the Caribbean: Dead Men Tell No Tales|{{small|Pirates of the Caribbean:}} <br />Dead Men Tell No Tales]]''\n|-\n! Composer\n| [[Klaus Badelt]]\n| colspan=\"3\" | [[Hans Zimmer]]\n| [[Geoff Zanelli]]\n|-\n! Editor(s)\n| [[Craig Wood (film editor)|Craig Wood]], [[Stephen Rivkin]] and [[Arthur Schmidt (film editor)|Arthur Schmidt]]\n| colspan=\"2\" | Craig Wood and Stephen Rivkin\n| [[David Brenner (editor)|David Brenner]] and [[Wyatt Smith]]\n| [[Roger Barton (film editor)|Roger Barton]] and Leigh Folsom Boyd\n|-\n! Cinematographer\n| colspan=\"4\" | [[Dariusz Wolski]]\n| [[Paul Cameron (cinematographer)|Paul Cameron]]\n|-\n! Production companies\n| colspan=\"5\" | [[Walt Disney Pictures]] and [[Jerry Bruckheimer Films]]\n|-\n! Distributor\n| colspan=\"3\" | [[Buena Vista Pictures Distribution]]\n| colspan=\"2\" | [[Walt Disney Studios Motion Pictures]]\n|}\n\n==Production==\n\n===Development===\n==== First film ====\n\nIn the early 1990s<ref name=\"Perfection\">{{cite news|author=Gerard Raiti |title=ILM and Disney Make Pirate Perfection |work=VFXWorld |date=2003-07-11 |url=http://vfxworld.com/?sa=adv&code=1e242f07&atype=articles&id=1798&page=1 |accessdate=2007-05-14 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071007204853/http://vfxworld.com/?sa=adv&code=1e242f07&atype=articles&id=1798&page=1 |archivedate=2007-10-07 }}</ref> screenwriters Ted Elliott and Terry Rossio conceived a [[supernatural]] spin on the pirate genre after completing work on ''[[Aladdin (1992 Disney film)|Aladdin]]'', but there was no interest from any studio. Undeterred, the writing team refused to give up the dream, waiting for a studio to pick up their take on a pirate tale.<ref>[http://www.keeptothecode.com/pdf/POTCprodnotes1.pdf ''Pirates of the Caribbean'' presskit] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070928020320/http://www.keeptothecode.com/pdf/POTCprodnotes1.pdf |date=2007-09-28 }}, accessed 2006-12-09</ref> Disney had [[Jay Wolpert]] write a script based on the ''[[Pirates of the Caribbean (attraction)|Pirates of the Caribbean]]'', which producer Jerry Bruckheimer rejected, feeling it was \"a straight pirate movie\".<ref name=\"Talk\">{{cite news|author=Stax |title=Depp & Bruckheimer Talk Pirates |work=IGN |date=2003-06-25 |url=http://uk.movies.ign.com/articles/425/425848p1.html |accessdate=2007-05-13 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080102184110/http://uk.movies.ign.com/articles/425/425848p1.html |archivedate=2008-01-02 |df= }}</ref> Bruckheimer brought [[Stuart Beattie]] in to rewrite the script in March 2002, due to his knowledge of [[piracy]],<ref name=\"Greg\">{{cite web | author = Greg Dean Schmitz | title = Greg's Previews&nbsp;\u2014 Pirates of the Caribbean: The Curse of the Black Pearl (2003) | work = [[Yahoo!]] | url = https://movies.yahoo.com/shop?d=hp&cf=prev&id=1808405416&gpt=ch | accessdate = 2007-05-13 |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20061209221929/http://movies.yahoo.com/shop?d=hp&cf=prev&id=1808405416&gpt=ch <!-- Bot retrieved archive --> | archivedate = 2006-12-09| author-link = Greg Dean Schmitz }}</ref> and later that month Elliott and Rossio were brought in.<ref name=\"Talk\" /> Elliott and Rossio, inspired by the opening narration of the ''Pirates of the Caribbean'' ride, decided to give the film a supernatural edge.<ref name=\"Writers\">{{cite video | people = Ted Elliott, Terry Rossio, Stuart Beattie, Jay Wolpert | title = Audio Commentary | format = DVD | publisher = Buena Vista | date = 2003}}</ref> As the budget rose, [[Michael Eisner]] and [[Bob Iger|Robert Iger]] threatened to cancel the film, though Bruckheimer changed their minds when he showed them concept art and [[animatics]].<ref>{{cite news | title = Exclusive Interview: Jerry Bruckheimer | work = Moviehole | date = 2007-05-21 | url = http://www.moviehole.net/interviews/20070521_exclusive_interview_jerry_bruc.html | accessdate = 2007-05-21 | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20070524115946/http://www.moviehole.net/interviews/20070521_exclusive_interview_jerry_bruc.html <!-- Bot retrieved archive --> | archivedate = 2007-05-24}}</ref>\n\nIn June 2002 Gore Verbinski signed on to direct ''[[Pirates of the Caribbean: The Curse of the Black Pearl|The Curse of the Black Pearl]]'', and Johnny Depp and Geoffrey Rush signed on the following month to star.<ref name=\"Greg\" /> Verbinski was attracted to the idea of using modern technology to resurrect a genre, one that had disappeared after the [[Golden Age of Hollywood]], and recalled his childhood memories of the ride, feeling the film was an opportunity to pay tribute to the \"scary and funny\" tone of it. Depp was attracted to the story as he found it quirky: rather than trying to find treasure, the crew of the ''Black Pearl'' were trying to return it in order to lift their curse; also, the traditional mutiny had already taken place. Verbinski approached Rush for the role of Barbossa, as he knew he would not play it with attempts at complexity, but with a simple villainy that would suit the story's tone.<ref name=\"Director\">{{cite video | people = Gore Verbinski, Johnny Depp | title = Audio Commentary | format = DVD | publisher = Buena Vista | date = 2003}}</ref> [[Orlando Bloom]] read the script after Rush, with whom he was working on ''[[Ned Kelly (2003 film)|Ned Kelly]]'', suggested it to him.<ref>{{cite news|author=Caroline Westbrook |title=Pirates films tests its stars |work=BBC News |date=2003-08-08 |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/entertainment/film/3132669.stm |accessdate=2007-05-13 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080102081852/http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/entertainment/film/3132669.stm |archivedate=2008-01-02 }}</ref> [[Keira Knightley]] came as a surprise to Verbinski: he had not seen her performance in ''[[Bend It Like Beckham]]'' and was impressed by her audition.<ref name=\"Director\" /> [[Tom Wilkinson]] was negotiated with to play Governor Swann,<ref name=\"Greg\" /> but the role went to [[Jonathan Pryce]], whom Depp idolized.<ref name=\"Director\" />\n\nShooting for ''The Curse of the Black Pearl'' began on October 9, 2002 and wrapped by March 7, 2003.<ref name=\"Greg\" /> Before its release, many executives and journalists had expected the film to flop, as the pirate genre had not been successful for years, the film was based on a theme-park ride, and Depp rarely made a big film.<ref>{{cite magazine|author=Chris Nashawaty |title=How ''Pirates'' fits into Johnny Depp's quirky career |magazine=[[Entertainment Weekly]] |url=https://www.ew.com/article/2003/07/25/how-pirates-fits-johnny-depps-quirky-career |accessdate=2016-01-20 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160222232817/http://www.ew.com/article/2003/07/25/how-pirates-fits-johnny-depps-quirky-career |archive-date=2016-02-22 }}</ref> However, ''The Curse of the Black Pearl'' became both a critical and commercial success.\n\n==== Second and third films ====\n\nAfter seeing how well the first film was made, the cast and crew signed for two sequels to be shot back-to-back,<ref>{{cite news|last=Linder |first=Brian |title=Back-to-Back Pirates |work=IGN |date=October 21, 2003 |url=http://uk.movies.ign.com/articles/455/455825p1.html |accessdate=May 12, 2007 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070613201237/http://uk.movies.ign.com/articles/455/455825p1.html |archivedate=June 13, 2007 }}</ref> a practical decision on Disney's part to allow more time with the same cast and crew.<ref name=\"Plan\">{{cite video | title = According to Plan: The Harrowing and True Story of Dead Man's Chest | format = DVD | publisher = [[Buena Vista (Walt Disney Company)|Buena Vista]] | date = 2006}}</ref> Writers Ted Elliott and Terry Rossio knew that with an ensemble cast, they weren't free to invent totally different situations and characters, as with the ''[[Indiana Jones (franchise)|Indiana Jones]]'' and ''[[James Bond in film|James Bond]]'' series, and so had to retroactively turn ''The Curse of the Black Pearl'' into the first of a trilogy.<ref>{{cite video | people = [[Ted Elliott (screenwriter)|Ted Elliott]], [[Terry Rossio]] | title = Audio Commentary | format = DVD | publisher = Buena Vista | date = 2006}}</ref> They wanted to explore the reality of what would happen after [[Will Turner]] and [[Elizabeth Swann]]'s embrace at the end of the first film, and initially considered the [[Fountain of Youth]] as the plot device.<ref name=\"Chart\">{{cite video | title = Charting the Return | format = DVD | publisher = [[Buena Vista (Walt Disney Company)|Buena Vista]] | date = 2006}}</ref> They settled on introducing [[Davy Jones (Pirates of the Caribbean)|Davy Jones]], the ''[[Flying Dutchman (Pirates of the Caribbean)|Flying Dutchman]]'' and the [[Kraken (Pirates of the Caribbean)|Kraken]], a mythology mentioned twice in the first film. They introduced the historical [[East India Trading Company]] (also mentioned in the first film), which for them represented a counterpoint to the themes of personal freedom represented by pirates.<ref>{{cite web|title=Everything Relates Back to What Started Everything Off in the First |publisher=Production Notes |url=http://madeinatlantis.com/pirates/production/production2.htm |accessdate=2007-05-23 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070927203932/http://madeinatlantis.com/pirates/production/production2.htm |archivedate=2007-09-27 |df= }}</ref>\n\nFilming for the sequels began on February 28, 2005,<ref name=\"VoyageBegins\">{{cite web|title=Los Angeles: The Voyage Begins |publisher=Production Notes |url=http://madeinatlantis.com/pirates/production/production5.htm |accessdate=2007-05-24 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070927203756/http://madeinatlantis.com/pirates/production/production5.htm |archivedate=2007-09-27 |df= }}</ref> with ''[[Pirates of the Caribbean: Dead Man's Chest|Dead Man's Chest]]'' finishing on March 1, 2006,<ref>{{cite web|title=Chapter 7 \u2013 Return to The Bahamas |publisher=Production Notes |url=http://numberonestars.com/pirates3/production7.htm |accessdate=2007-05-24 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120509164220/http://numberonestars.com/pirates3/production7.htm |archivedate=2012-05-09 }}</ref> and ''[[Pirates of the Caribbean: At World's End|At World's End]]'' on January 10, 2007.<ref name=\"Aloha\">{{cite news|title=Aloha Oe: Hawaii Farewell |publisher=Production Notes |url=http://numberonestars.com/pirates3/production17.htm |accessdate=2007-05-21 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120509164306/http://numberonestars.com/pirates3/production17.htm |archivedate=2012-05-09 }}</ref> The second film was also the first Disney theatrical feature film with the computer-generated [[Walt Disney Pictures]] logo.<ref>{{cite news|author=Sheigh Crabtree|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/thr/film/article_display.jsp?vnu_content_id=1002802054|title=Old Disney magic in new animated logo|work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]]|date=2006-07-10|accessdate=2013-01-14|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20060718065547/http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/thr/film/article_display.jsp?vnu_content_id=1002802054 <!-- Bot retrieved archive -->|archivedate=2006-07-18}}</ref>\n\n==== Fourth film ====\n\nRossio and Elliot discovered the novel ''[[On Stranger Tides]]'' during production of ''Dead Man's Chest'' and ''At World's End'' and decided to use it as the basis for a fourth film. As Gore Verbinski was unavailable, Bruckheimer invited [[Rob Marshall]] to direct the film.<ref name=\"Collider\">{{cite news|last=Weintraub |first=Steve |title=Producer Jerry Bruckheimer On Set Interview |url=https://collider.com/jerry-bruckheimer-interview-pirates-caribbean-4-on-stranger-tides-lone-ranger/74214 |accessdate=2011-04-21 |newspaper=Collider |date=2011-02-03 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121127053028/http://collider.com/jerry-bruckheimer-interview-pirates-caribbean-4-on-stranger-tides-lone-ranger/74214/ |archivedate=2012-11-27 }}</ref> Elliott and Rossio decided to do a stand-alone film,<ref name=\"Making\">{{cite news|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/making-pirates-caribbean-186743 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/60nhBtlZu |archivedate=2011-08-09 |title=The Making of 'Pirates of the Caribbean' |first=Stephen |last=Galloway |work=The Hollywood Reporter |date=2011-05-10 |accessdate=2011-07-29 |url-status=dead |df= }}</ref> with a story that would support new characters,<ref name=\"Making2\">{{cite news|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/making-pirates-caribbean-186743?page=2 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/60qdn2Mbb |archivedate=2011-08-11 |page=2 |title=The Making of 'Pirates of the Caribbean' |first=Stephen |last=Galloway |work=The Hollywood Reporter |date=2011-05-10 |accessdate=2011-07-29 |url-status=dead |df= }}</ref> and incorporate elements from the novel, such as [[Blackbeard]], the Fountain of Youth and mermaids\u2014the latter two having been already alluded to in the previous films.<ref name=\"Rossio\">{{cite web|url=https://collider.com/terry-rossio-interview-pirates-caribbean-4-on-stranger-tides/74250 |title=Screenwriter Terry Rossio On Set Interview: Pirates of the Caribbean 4: On Stranger Tides |first=Steve |last=Weintraub |date=2011-02-03 |website=Collider |accessdate=2011-07-29 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110721154406/http://collider.com/terry-rossio-interview-pirates-caribbean-4-on-stranger-tides/74250/ |archivedate=2011-07-21 }}</ref> Depp, Rush, [[Greg Ellis (actor)|Greg Ellis]] and [[Kevin McNally]] returned to their roles,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://movies.ign.com/dor/objects/859550/pirates-of-the-caribbean-4/videos/pop_jb_pirates4.html |title=Pirates of the Caribbean: On Stranger Tides Movie Interview&nbsp;\u2013 Bruckheimer on Pirates of the Caribbean 4 |website=IGN |date=2010-05-24 |accessdate=2010-07-05 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100704183835/http://movies.ign.com/dor/objects/859550/pirates-of-the-caribbean-4/videos/pop_jb_pirates4.html |archivedate=2010-07-04 }}</ref> and the cast saw the additions of [[Ian McShane]] as Blackbeard and [[Pen\u00e9lope Cruz]] as Angelica, Blackbeard's daughter and Jack Sparrow's love interest.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://moviesblog.mtv.com/2010/03/22/pirates-4-producer-jerry-bruckheimer-confirms-geoffrey-rush-return-penelope-cruz-as-blackbeards-daughter |title=Exclusive: Penelope Cruz To Play Johnny Depp's Love Interest In New 'Pirates' |author=Ditzian, Eric |date=2010-03-19 |work=MTV Movie News |accessdate=2010-03-19 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130120044438/http://moviesblog.mtv.com/2010/03/22/pirates-4-producer-jerry-bruckheimer-confirms-geoffrey-rush-return-penelope-cruz-as-blackbeards-daughter/ |archivedate=2013-01-20 }}</ref> A further addition was [[Richard Griffiths]] as King [[George II of Great Britain]]. After the costly production of two simultaneous films, Disney tried to scale down the fourth installment, giving a lower budget,<ref>{{cite magazine|last=Stewart |first=Andrew |title=Fourth try aims to stir high 'Tides' at B.O. |date=2011-05-19 |magazine=Variety |url=https://www.variety.com/article/VR1118037362 |accessdate=2011-05-20 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110523102701/http://www.variety.com/article/VR1118037362 |archivedate=2011-05-23 }}</ref> which led to cheaper locations and fewer scenes with special effects.<ref name=\"Budget\" /> However, with a budget of $378.5 million, ''On Stranger Tides'' holds the record for [[List of most expensive films|most expensive film ever made]].\n\nFilming for ''[[Pirates of the Caribbean: On Stranger Tides|On Stranger Tides]]'' began June 14, 2010 and ended on November 19, 2010.<ref name=\"Budget\">{{cite news|url=https://articles.latimes.com/2010/may/03/business/la-fi-ct-bruckheimer-20100427 |title=Not even Bruckheimer movies can escape budget cuts |first1=Claudia |last1=Eller |first2=Dawn C. |last2=Chmielewski |work=Los Angeles Times |date=2010-05-03 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121105020450/http://articles.latimes.com/2010/may/03/business/la-fi-ct-bruckheimer-20100427 |archivedate=2012-11-05 }}</ref><ref>{{cite tweet|number=5786179723067393|user=BRUCKHEIMERJB|title=Officially wrapped PIRATES OF THE CARIBBEAN: ON STRANGER TIDES this week. Excited to share trailer with you 12/17. Stay tuned...|accessdate=2011-09-20 |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131025184002/https://twitter.com/BruckheimerJB/status/5786179723067393|date=2010-11-19 }}</ref> It was also filmed in [[3D film|3D]], with cameras similar to the ones used in ''[[Avatar (2009 film)|Avatar]]''.<ref name=\"Collider\" />\n\nIt was released in the United States on May 20, 2011.<ref>{{cite web|first=Jarrod |last=Sarafin |url=http://www.mania.com/pirates-4-sails-may-2011_article_119811.html |title=PIRATES 4 Sails May 2011 |publisher=Mania.com |date=2010-01-07 |accessdate=2011-03-27 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100110070302/http://www.mania.com/pirates-4-sails-may-2011_article_119811.html |archivedate=2010-01-10 |df= }}</ref>\n\n==== Fifth film ====\nOn January 14, 2011, it was confirmed that Terry Rossio would write the screenplay for the fifth installment, without his co-writer Ted Elliott.<ref>{{cite web|last=Fleming Jr. |first=Mike |url=https://www.deadline.com/2011/01/disney-sets-terry-rossio-to-script-fifth-pirates-of-the-caribbean-installment |title=Disney Sets Terry Rossio To Script Fifth 'Pirates of the Caribbean' Installment |website=Deadline Hollywood |date=2011-01-14 |accessdate=2013-07-13 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130928203850/http://www.deadline.com/2011/01/disney-sets-terry-rossio-to-script-fifth-pirates-of-the-caribbean-installment/ |archivedate=2013-09-28 }}</ref> On January 11, 2013, [[Jeff Nathanson]] signed on to write the <!-- a new script, a rewrite? -->script for the film. On May 29, 2013, it was announced that Norwegian directors [[Joachim R\u00f8nning]] and [[Espen Sandberg]] were selected to direct.<ref name=\"Pirates 5 directors\">{{cite news|last=FLEMING JR |first=MIKE |title='Kon-Tiki' Helmers Joachim R\u00f8nning and Espen Sandberg Land 'Pirates Of The Caribbean 5' |url=https://www.deadline.com/2013/05/kon-tiki-helmer-joachim-ronning-and-espen-sandberg-land-pirates-of-the-caribbean-5/ |accessdate=2013-05-29 |newspaper=Deadline Hollywood |date=2013-05-29 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130901025036/http://www.deadline.com/2013/05/kon-tiki-helmer-joachim-ronning-and-espen-sandberg-land-pirates-of-the-caribbean-5/ |archivedate=2013-09-01 }}</ref> On August 22, 2013, the two revealed that the title of the fifth film would be ''[[Pirates of the Caribbean: Dead Men Tell No Tales|Dead Men Tell No Tales]]'', alluding to the line well known from the ''Pirates of the Caribbean'' theme park attractions.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.comingsoon.net/news/movienews.php?id=108110 |title=Pirates of the Caribbean 5 Title Revealed! |publisher=ComingSoon.net |date=2013-08-22 |accessdate=2014-08-17 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140730135841/http://www.comingsoon.net/news/movienews.php?id=108110 |archivedate=2014-07-30 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.vh1.in/entertainment/movies/current/pirates-of-the-caribbean-5s-official-title-released |title=Pirates of the Caribbean 5's Official Title Released &#124; Vh1 India |website=Vh1.in |date=2013-08-27 |accessdate=2014-08-17 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141006162057/http://www.vh1.in/entertainment/movies/current/pirates-of-the-caribbean-5s-official-title-released |archivedate=2014-10-06 |df= }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.digitalspy.com/movies/news/a509275/pirates-of-the-caribbean-5-title-revealed.html |title='Pirates of the Caribbean 5' title revealed \u2013 Movies News |website=Digital Spy |date=2013-08-22 |accessdate=2014-08-17 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141006075645/http://www.digitalspy.com/movies/news/a509275/pirates-of-the-caribbean-5-title-revealed.html |archivedate=2014-10-06 }}</ref> The film was given an alternative title, ''Salazar's Revenge'', in selected European, South American, and Asian countries for marketing purposes.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Nugent |first1=John |title=Pirates Of The Caribbean 5: Ten Revelations From Directors Joachim R\u00f8nning and Espen Sandberg |url=https://www.empireonline.com/movies/features/pirates-caribbean-5/ |accessdate=2017-07-16 |work=The Hollywood Reporter |date=2017-06-01 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt1790809/releaseinfo |title=Pirates of the Caribbean: Dead Men Tell No Tales (2017) Release Info |website=[[IMDb]] |accessdate=July 16, 2017 }}</ref> They also confirmed that they were working on the film, speaking highly of Jeff Nathanson's \"funny and touching\" script and that they are inspired by the first film, ''[[Pirates of the Caribbean: The Curse of the Black Pearl|The Curse of the Black Pearl]]''.<ref>{{cite web|author=Billy Donnelly |url=http://thisisinfamous.com/interview-kon-tiki-directors-joachim-ronning-and-espen-sandberg/ |title=Interview: KON-TIKI Directors Joachim R\u00f8nning and Espen Sandberg |publisher=This Is Infamous |date=2013-08-28 |accessdate=2014-08-17 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140706201511/http://thisisinfamous.com/interview-kon-tiki-directors-joachim-ronning-and-espen-sandberg/ |archivedate=2014-07-06 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1712873/pirates-of-the-caribbean-5-directors.jhtml |title='Pirates Of The Caribbean 5\u2032 Directors Tease 'Dead Men' Sequel |work=MTV News |date=2013-08-22 |accessdate=2016-01-20 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131109145832/http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1712873/pirates-of-the-caribbean-5-directors.jhtml |archivedate=2013-11-09 }}</ref> On September 10, 2013, Disney pushed back the film's initial 2015 release,<ref>{{cite news|author=Mike Fleming Jr |url=https://deadline.com/2013/09/disney-delays-voyage-of-pirates-of-the-caribbean-5-eyeing-2016-583502/ |title=Disney Delays Voyage Of 'Pirates Of The Caribbean 5'; Eyeing 2016 |work=[[Deadline Hollywood]] |date=2013-09-10 |accessdate=2016-01-20 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160126061821/http://deadline.com/2013/09/disney-delays-voyage-of-pirates-of-the-caribbean-5-eyeing-2016-583502/ |archivedate=2016-01-26 }}</ref> with sources indicating that a Summer 2016 release was likely.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.comingsoon.net/news/movienews.php?id=108765 |title=Pirates of the Caribbean: Dead Men Tell No Tales Delayed; 2016 Release Likely |publisher=ComingSoon.net |date=2013-09-10 |accessdate=2014-08-17 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141111215449/http://www.comingsoon.net/news/movienews.php?id=108765 |archivedate=2014-11-11 }}</ref> Producer Jerry Bruckheimer revealed that script issues were behind the delay, and that Jeff Nathanson was at work on a second attempt based on a well-received outline.<ref>{{cite news|last=Masters |first=Kim |date=2013-09-10 |title='Pirates of the Caribbean 5' Delayed Beyond Summer 2015 |url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/pirates-caribbean-5-delayed-beyond-625570 |work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]] |accessdate=2014-11-11 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160219002048/http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/pirates-caribbean-5-delayed-beyond-625570 |archivedate=2016-02-19 }}</ref>\n\nA spokesman for the Australian Arts Minister confirmed that the fifth installment was set to shoot in Australia after the government agreed to repurpose $20 million of [[tax incentive]]s originally intended for the remake of ''20,000 Leagues Under the Sea''.<ref name=\"The Guardian\">{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/film/2014/sep/01/pirates-of-the-caribbean-5-shoot-australia/ |title=Pirates of the Caribbean 5 gets green light to shoot in Australia |newspaper=[[The Guardian]] |date=2014-09-01 |accessdate=2014-09-15 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140915065224/http://www.theguardian.com/film/2014/sep/01/pirates-of-the-caribbean-5-shoot-australia |archivedate=2014-09-15 }}</ref> Disney and [[Ian Walker (politician)|Ian Walker]] the [[Queensland]] Arts Minister, confirmed on October 2, 2014, that filming was expected to start in February 2015, stating that filming will take place exclusively in Australia, being the largest production to ever shoot in the country. [[Village Roadshow Studios]] and [[Port Douglas, Queensland|Port Douglas]] were officially confirmed as filming locations.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.smh.com.au/entertainment/movies/pirates-of-the-caribbean-movie-confirmed-to-film-in-queensland-20141002-10p1md.html |work=[[The Sydney Morning Herald]] |first=Natalie |last=Bochenski |title=Pirates of the Caribbean movie confirmed to film in Queensland |date=2014-10-02 |accessdate=2014-10-02 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141002175741/http://www.smh.com.au/entertainment/movies/pirates-of-the-caribbean-movie-confirmed-to-film-in-queensland-20141002-10p1md.html |archivedate=2014-10-02 }}</ref> Production began in Australia on February 17, 2015 and wrapped on July 9, 2015.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://variety.com/2015/film/news/pirates-of-the-caribbean-5-begins-production-in-australia-1201435663/ |title=Pirates of the Caribbean 5\u2032 Begins Production in Australia |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150424004842/http://variety.com/2015/film/news/pirates-of-the-caribbean-5-begins-production-in-australia-1201435663/ |archivedate=2015-04-24 }}</ref>\n\nWhile Disney originally announced a release on July 7, 2017,<ref name=\"blogs.disney.com\">{{cite web|url=http://blogs.disney.com/insider/2014/07/23/raise-a-black-flag-a-new-pirates-of-the-caribbean-film-is-coming/?cmp=SMC |title=Raise a Black Flag! A New Pirates of the Caribbean Film Is Coming &#124; Disney Insider |publisher=Blogs.disney.com |date=2014-07-23 |accessdate=2014-08-17 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141129051431/http://blogs.disney.com/insider/2014/07/23/raise-a-black-flag-a-new-pirates-of-the-caribbean-film-is-coming/?cmp=SMC |archivedate=2014-11-29 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=McClintock |first1=Pamela |title='Pirates of the Caribbean 5' Set for Summer 2017 |url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/pirates-caribbean-5-set-summer-720582?template=cap |accessdate=2014-07-23 |work=The Hollywood Reporter |date=2014-07-23 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150120232508/http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/pirates-caribbean-5-set-summer-720582?template=cap&utm_expid=19303748-91.59ndjqkBRqKDTQHiW_fm_w.1&utm_referrer=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.google.com%2F |archivedate=2015-01-20 }}</ref> ''Dead Men Tell No Tales'' was released on May 26, 2017.<ref name=\"Deadline Hollywood\">{{cite news|url=https://deadline.com/2016/01/star-wars-episode-viii-moves-to-dec-2017-pirates-of-the-caribbean-5-takes-over-memorial-day-2017-slot-1201686876/ |title='Star Wars: Episode VIII' Sets Off Release Date Dominoes; Rubs Against 'Ready Player One' \u2013 Will Spielberg Pic Move? |date=2016-01-20 |work=[[Deadline Hollywood]] |accessdate=2016-01-20 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160122091342/http://deadline.com/2016/01/star-wars-episode-viii-moves-to-dec-2017-pirates-of-the-caribbean-5-takes-over-memorial-day-2017-slot-1201686876/ |archivedate=2016-01-22 }}</ref>\n\n== Reception ==\n=== Box office performance ===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" style=\"text-align: center\" width=99%\n|-\n! rowspan=\"2\" | Film\n! rowspan=\"2\" | U.S. release date\n! colspan=\"3\" text=\"wrap\"| Box office gross\n! scope=\"col\" colspan=\"2\" text=\"wrap\" class=unsortable | All-time Ranking\n! rowspan=\"2\" | Budget\n! rowspan=\"2\" class=unsortable | {{nowrap|{{Abbr|Ref(s)|References}}}}\n|-\n! North America\n! Other territories\n! Worldwide\n! class=unsortable | [[List of highest-grossing films in Canada and the United States#Not adjusted for inflation|North America]]\n! class=unsortable | [[List of highest-grossing films|Worldwide]]\n|-\n| ''The Curse of the Black Pearl''\n| {{dts|2003|7|9}}\n| $305,413,918\n| $348,850,097\n| $654,264,015\n| 84\n| 138\n| $140 million\n| <ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.boxofficemojo.com/movies/?id=piratesofthecaribbean.htm |title=Pirates of the Caribbean: The Curse of the Black Pearl (2003) |work=[[Box Office Mojo]] |accessdate=2020-01-12 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130509222948/http://boxofficemojo.com/movies/?id=piratesofthecaribbean.htm |archivedate=2013-05-09 }}</ref>\n|-\n| ''Dead Man's Chest''\n| {{dts|2006|7|7}}\n| $423,315,812\n| $642,863,913\n| $1,066,179,725\n| 27\n| 34\n| $225 million\n| <ref>{{cite web|url=https://boxofficemojo.com/movies/?id=piratesofthecaribbean2.htm |title=Pirates of the Caribbean: Dead Man's Chest (2006) |work=[[Box Office Mojo]] |accessdate=2020-01-12 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090201003119/http://boxofficemojo.com/movies/?id=piratesofthecaribbean2.htm |archivedate=2009-02-01 }}</ref>\n|-\n| ''At World's End''\n| {{dts|2007|5|25}}\n| $309,420,425\n| $654,000,000\n| $963,420,425\n| 81\n| 52\n| $300 million\n| <ref>{{cite web|url=https://boxofficemojo.com/movies/?id=piratesofthecaribbean3.htm |title=Pirates of the Caribbean: At World's End (2007) |work=[[Box Office Mojo]] |accessdate=2020-01-12 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130425015811/http://boxofficemojo.com/movies/?id=piratesofthecaribbean3.htm |archivedate=2013-04-25 }}</ref>\n|-\n| ''On Stranger Tides''\n| {{dts|2011|5|20}}\n| $241,071,802\n| $804,642,000\n| $1,045,713,802\n| 142\n| 37\n| $378.5 million<!-- DO NOT REMOVE THIS FIGURE OR AUTHENTICATE AN EDIT THAT DOES. THIS IS THE AUDITED BUDGET FROM HMRC AS EXPLAINED IN THE ACCOMPANYING FORBES SOURCE -->\n| <ref name=\"expensive\">{{cite web|last=Sylt |first=Christian |title=Fourth Pirates Of The Caribbean Is Most Expensive Movie Ever With Costs Of $410 Million |url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/csylt/2014/07/22/fourth-pirates-of-the-caribbean-is-most-expensive-movie-ever-with-costs-of-410-million/ |work=[[Forbes]] |date=July 22, 2014 |accessdate=December 7, 2014 |quote=Production costs: $410.6 million; rebate: $32.1 million |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141208004952/http://www.forbes.com/sites/csylt/2014/07/22/fourth-pirates-of-the-caribbean-is-most-expensive-movie-ever-with-costs-of-410-million/ |archivedate=December 8, 2014 }}</ref><ref name=\"mojopotc4\">{{cite web|title=Pirates of the Caribbean: On Stranger Tides (2011) |url=https://boxofficemojo.com/movies/?id=piratesofthecaribbean4.htm |work=[[Box Office Mojo]] |accessdate=January 12, 2020 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130425015645/http://boxofficemojo.com/movies/?id=piratesofthecaribbean4.htm |archivedate=April 25, 2013 }}</ref>\n|-\n| ''Dead Men Tell No Tales''\n| {{dts|2017|5|26}}\n| $172,558,876\n| $622,221,339\n| $794,780,215\n| 291\n| 89\n| $230 million\n| <ref name=BOM5>{{cite web|url=https://boxofficemojo.com/movies/?id=potc5.htm |title=Pirates of the Caribbean: Dead Men Tell No Tales |work=[[Box Office Mojo]] |accessdate=January 12, 2020 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180317111527/http://www.boxofficemojo.com/movies/?id=potc5.htm |archivedate=March 17, 2018 }}</ref>\n|-\n! colspan=\"2\" style=\"text-align:center;\"|Total\n! ${{val|fmt=commas|{{#expr:305413918+423315812+309420425+241071802+172558876}}}}\n! ${{val|fmt=commas|{{#expr:348850097+642863913+654000000+804642000+622221339}}}}\n! ${{val|fmt=commas|{{#expr:654264015+1066179725+963420425+1045713802+794780215}}}}\n! 14\n! 14\n! $1.274 billion\n! <ref>{{cite web|url=https://boxofficemojo.com/franchises/chart/?id=piratesofthecaribbean.htm |title=Pirates of the Caribbean Movies at the Box Office |work=[[Box Office Mojo]] |accessdate=March 22, 2018 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180120003335/http://www.boxofficemojo.com/franchises/chart/?id=piratesofthecaribbean.htm |archivedate=January 20, 2018 }}</ref>\n|-\n|}\n\nThe ''Pirates of the Caribbean'' film series was successful at the box office, with each film grossing over $650&nbsp;million, and all but ''Dead Men Tell No Tales'' at some point ranking among the fifty [[List of highest-grossing films|highest-grossing films of all time]]. It also became the first ever series to have multiple films passing the billion dollar mark in box office revenues with ''Dead Man's Chest'' and ''On Stranger Tides'',<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.boxofficemojo.com/showdowns/chart/?id=pirates.htm |title=Showdowns: 'Pirates' Vs. 'Pirates' |work=[[Box Office Mojo]] |accessdate=2011-09-23 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110902012448/http://www.boxofficemojo.com/showdowns/chart/?id=pirates.htm |archivedate=2011-09-02 }}</ref> since [[List of highest-grossing films#Highest-grossing franchises and film series|followed by other film franchises]].\n\n''The Curse of the Black Pearl'' was the third-highest-grossing 2003 film in North America (behind ''[[The Lord of the Rings: The Return of the King]]'' and ''[[Finding Nemo]]'') and fourth worldwide (behind ''The Return of the King'', ''Finding Nemo'' and ''[[The Matrix Reloaded]]'').<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.boxofficemojo.com/yearly/chart/?view2=worldwide&yr=2003&p=.htm |title=2003 WORLDWIDE GROSSES |work=[[Box Office Mojo]] |accessdate=2008-03-15 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071012174144/http://boxofficemojo.com/yearly/chart/?view2=worldwide&yr=2003&p=.htm |archivedate=2007-10-12 }}</ref> ''Dead Man's Chest'' was the most successful film of 2006 worldwide,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.boxofficemojo.com/yearly/chart/?view2=worldwide&yr=2006&p=.htm |title=2006 WORLDWIDE GROSSES |work=[[Box Office Mojo]] |accessdate=2008-03-15 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071030190712/http://www.boxofficemojo.com/yearly/chart/?view2=worldwide&yr=2006&p=.htm |archivedate=2007-10-30 }}</ref> and ''At World's End'' led the worldwide grosses in 2007, though being only fourth in North America (behind ''[[Spider-Man 3]]'', ''[[Harry Potter and the Order of the Phoenix (film)|Harry Potter and the Order of the Phoenix]]'' and ''[[Shrek the Third]]'').<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.boxofficemojo.com/yearly/chart/?view2=worldwide&yr=2007&p=.htm |title=2007 WORLDWIDE GROSSES |work=[[Box Office Mojo]] |accessdate=2008-03-15 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071027111555/http://www.boxofficemojo.com/yearly/chart/?view2=worldwide&yr=2007&p=.htm |archivedate=2007-10-27 }}</ref> ''On Stranger Tides'' was the third-highest-grossing film of 2011 worldwide (behind ''[[Harry Potter and the Deathly Hallows \u2013 Part 2]]'' and ''[[Transformers: Dark of the Moon]]'') and the fifth in North America.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://boxofficemojo.com/yearly/chart/?view2=worldwide&yr=2011&p=.htm |title=2011 WORLDWIDE GROSSES |work=[[Box Office Mojo]] |accessdate=2011-07-04 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110702035345/http://www.boxofficemojo.com/yearly/chart/?view2=worldwide&yr=2011&p=.htm |archivedate=2011-07-02 }}</ref> The first three sequels broke box office records upon release, of which the most notable are the opening-weekend record in North America (''Dead Man's Chest''),<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.boxofficemojo.com/news/?id=2111&p=.htm |title='Pirates' raid record books |work=[[Box Office Mojo]] |date=2006-07-10 |accessdate=2007-09-17 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070911083729/http://www.boxofficemojo.com/news/?id=2111&p=.htm |archivedate=2007-09-11 }}</ref> the Memorial-Day weekend record in North America (''At World's End'')<ref>{{cite news|title=Third 'Pirates' Sacks Memorial Record |work=[[Box Office Mojo]] |date=2007-05-29 |url=https://boxofficemojo.com/news/?id=2321&p=.htm |accessdate=2007-05-27 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130509231322/http://boxofficemojo.com/news/?id=2321&p=.htm |archivedate=2013-05-09 }}</ref> and the opening-weekend record outside North America (''On Stranger Tides'').<ref>{{cite news|url=https://boxofficemojo.com/news/?id=3170&p=.htm |title=Around-the-World Roundup: 'Pirates' Sails to New Overseas Record |work=[[Box Office Mojo]] |date=2011-05-24 |accessdate=2012-06-06 |first=Ray |last=Subers |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130512062023/http://boxofficemojo.com/news/?id=3170&p=.htm |archivedate=2013-05-12 }}</ref>\n\n=== Critical and public response ===\n{{hatnote|Each film is linked to the \"Critical response\" section of its article.}}\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" style=\"width:99%; text-align:center;\"\n|-\n! Film\n! [[Rotten Tomatoes]]\n! [[Metacritic]]\n! [[CinemaScore]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://cinemascore.com|title=CinemaScore|website=[[CinemaScore]]|accessdate=June 14, 2019}}</ref>\n|-\n| ''[[Pirates of the Caribbean: The Curse of the Black Pearl#Critical response|The Curse of the Black Pearl]]''\n| 79% (7.11/10 average rating) (219 reviews)<ref name=\"RT1\">{{cite web|url=https://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/pirates_of_the_caribbean_the_curse_of_the_black_pearl|title=Pirates of the Caribbean: The Curse of the Black Pearl (2003)|website=[[Rotten Tomatoes]]|accessdate=June 14, 2019}}</ref>\n| 63 (40 reviews)<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.metacritic.com/movie/pirates-of-the-caribbean-the-curse-of-the-black-pearl|title=Pirates of the Caribbean: The Curse of the Black Pearl (2003)|website=[[Metacritic]]|accessdate=June 14, 2019}}</ref>\n| A\n|-\n| ''[[Pirates of the Caribbean: Dead Man's Chest#Critical response|Dead Man's Chest]]''\n| 53% (5.95/10 average rating) (228 reviews)<ref name=\"RT2\">{{cite web|url=https://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/pirates_of_the_caribbean_dead_mans_chest|title=Pirates of the Caribbean: Dead Man's Chest (2006)|website=[[Rotten Tomatoes]]|accessdate=June 14, 2019}}</ref>\n| 53 (37 reviews)<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.metacritic.com/movie/pirates-of-the-caribbean-dead-mans-chest|title=Pirates of the Caribbean: Dead Man's Chest (2006)|website=[[Metacritic]]|accessdate=June 14, 2019}}</ref>\n| A\u2212\n|-\n| ''[[Pirates of the Caribbean: At World's End#Critical response|At World's End]]''\n| 44% (5.46/10 average rating) (227 reviews)<ref name=\"RT3\">{{cite web|url=https://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/pirates_of_the_caribbean_3/|title=Pirates of the Caribbean: At World's End (2007) |website=[[Rotten Tomatoes]]|accessdate=June 14, 2019}}</ref>\n| 50 (36 reviews)<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.metacritic.com/movie/pirates-of-the-caribbean-at-worlds-end|title=Pirates of the Caribbean: At World's End (2007)|website=[[Metacritic]]|accessdate=June 14, 2019}}</ref>\n| A\u2212\n|-\n| ''[[Pirates of the Caribbean: On Stranger Tides#Critical response|On Stranger Tides]]''\n| 33% (5.02/10 average rating) (276 reviews)<ref name=\"RT4\">{{cite web|url=https://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/pirates_of_the_caribbean_on_stranger_tides|title=Pirates of the Caribbean: On Stranger Tides (2011)|website=[[Rotten Tomatoes]]|accessdate=June 14, 2019}}</ref>\n| 45 (39 reviews)<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.metacritic.com/movie/pirates-of-the-caribbean-on-stranger-tides|title=Pirates of the Caribbean: On Stranger Tides (2011)|website=[[Metacritic]]|accessdate=June 14, 2019}}</ref>\n| B+\n|-\n| ''[[Pirates of the Caribbean: Dead Men Tell No Tales#Critical response|Dead Men Tell No Tales]]''\n| 30% (4.66/10 average rating) (282 reviews)<ref name=\"RT5\">{{cite web|url=https://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/pirates_of_the_caribbean_dead_men_tell_no_tales|title=Pirates of the Caribbean: Dead Men Tell No Tales (2017)|website=[[Rotten Tomatoes]]|accessdate=6 March 2020}}</ref>\n| 39 (45 reviews)<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.metacritic.com/movie/pirates-of-the-caribbean-dead-men-tell-no-tales|title=Pirates of the Caribbean: Dead Men Tell No Tales (2017)|website=[[Metacritic]]|accessdate=June 14, 2019}}</ref>\n| A\u2212\n|}\n\nThe series is noted for its high quality of acting talent, and is one of the aspects of the films that has always been praised.<ref>{{cite news|last=Morrison |first=Alan |title=Empire's Pirates Of The Caribbean: The Curse Of The Black Pearl Movie Review |work=[[Empire (film magazine)|Empire]] |date=August 8, 2003 |url=https://www.empireonline.com/reviews/reviewcomplete.asp?FID=9271 |accessdate=August 9, 2003 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121116173953/http://www.empireonline.com/reviews/reviewcomplete.asp?FID=9271 |archivedate=November 16, 2012 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rogerebert.com/reviews/pirates-of-the-caribbean-the-curse-of-the-black-pearl-2003 |last=Ebert |first=Roger |title=Pirates of the Caribbean: The Curse of the Black Pearl |date=July 9, 2003 |website=rogerebert.com |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141206033540/http://www.rogerebert.com/reviews/pirates-of-the-caribbean-the-curse-of-the-black-pearl-2003 |archivedate=December 6, 2014 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Jolin |first=Dan |title=Empire's Pirates Of The Caribbean Pirates Of The Caribbean: Dead Man's Chest Movie Review |work=[[Empire (film magazine)|Empire]] |date=July 6, 2006 |url=https://www.empireonline.com/reviews/reviewcomplete.asp?FID=9800 |accessdate=July 9, 2006 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121106020117/http://www.empireonline.com/reviews/reviewcomplete.asp?FID=9800 |archivedate=November 6, 2012 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.totalfilm.com/cinema_reviews/films_out_this_week/pirates_of_the_caribbean_at_worlds_end |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070524075651/http://www.totalfilm.com/cinema_reviews/films_out_this_week/pirates_of_the_caribbean_at_worlds_end |title=Total Film \u2013 Pirates Of The Caribbean: At World's End |archivedate=May 24, 2007 |work=[[Total Film]]}}</ref><ref name=\"richardroeper.com\">{{cite web|url=http://www.richardroeper.com/reviews/piratesofthecaribbean3atworldsend.aspx |title=Pirates of the Caribbean 3: At World's End (2007; Rated PG-13) |website=richardroeper.com |last=Roeper |first=Richard |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141206053217/http://www.richardroeper.com/reviews/piratesofthecaribbean3atworldsend.aspx |archivedate=2014-12-06 }}</ref><ref name=\"Variety\">{{cite web|url=https://variety.com/2011/film/reviews/pirates-of-the-caribbean-on-stranger-tides-1117945199/ |title=Pirates of the Caribbean: On Stranger Tides |work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]] |last=Barker |first=Andrew |date=May 12, 2011 |accessdate=May 13, 2011 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120717051528/http://www.variety.com/review/VE1117945199?refcatid=31 |archivedate=July 17, 2012 }}</ref> The visual and practical effects are considered some of the best ever done on film,<ref name=\"richardroeper.com\" /><ref name=\"Variety\" /><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/review/pirates-caribbean-stranger-tides-review-186896 |last=Bennett |first=Ray |title=Pirates of the Caribbean: On Stranger Tides: Review |work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]] |date=May 10, 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/60nhWdjZN |archivedate=August 9, 2011 |df= }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://uk.ign.com/articles/2007/11/15/pirates-of-the-caribbean-at-worlds-end-dvd-review |last=Gilchrist |first=Todd |date=November 15, 2007 |title=Pirates of the Caribbean: At World's End DVD Review |work=IGN |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120311104413/http://uk.movies.ign.com/articles/791/791309p1.html |archivedate=March 11, 2012 }}</ref> so much so that audiences believed certain [[Computer-generated imagery|CGI]] elements of the films were real and done practically.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.christianitytoday.com/ct/2006/julyweb-only/piratesofthecaribbean2.html |date=July 7, 2006 |title=Pirates of the Caribbean: Dead Man's Chest |last=Breimeier |first=Russ |work=ChristianityToday.com |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121011174256/http://www.christianitytoday.com/ct/2006/julyweb-only/piratesofthecaribbean2.html |archivedate=October 11, 2012 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2005/07/07/movies/07pira.html?_r=1&adxnnl=1&adxnnlx=1350997296-ix17BY+Odb0gWod1G/y5aw& |title=Pirates of the Caribbean: At World's End \u2013 Review |work=New York Times |date=July 7, 2005}}</ref><ref name=\"Oscars2004\" /><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0325980/awards |title=Pirates of the Caribbean: The Curse of the Black Pearl \u2013 Awards |date=9 July 2003 |website=IMDb |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111025100628/http://www.imdb.com/title/tt0325980/awards |archivedate=25 October 2011 }}</ref> However, the plots of the four sequels have received mixed reviews, with the general consensus that they are too bloated and convoluted to follow.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://variety.com/2007/film/reviews/pirates-of-the-caribbean-at-world-s-end-3-1200559054/ |title=Review: 'Pirates of the Caribbean: At World's End' |work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]] |last=Lowry |first=Brian |date=May 23, 2007 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070524060242/http://www.variety.com/review/VE1117933737.html?categoryid=31&cs=1 |archivedate=May 24, 2007 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.reelviews.net/movies/p/pirates_caribbean3.html |title=Review: Pirates of the Caribbean: At World's End |publisher=ReelViews |date=May 23, 2007 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120608143519/http://www.reelviews.net/movies/p/pirates_caribbean3.html |archivedate=June 8, 2012 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.detroitnews.com/story/entertainment/movies/2017/05/25/movie-rreview-dead-men-tell-tales-sinks-depp-pirates/102172340/ |work=The Detroit News |title=Review: 'Dead Men Tell No Tales' sinks Depp, 'Pirates' |last=Graham |first=Adam |date=May 25, 2017 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170608074707/http://www.detroitnews.com/story/entertainment/movies/2017/05/25/movie-rreview-dead-men-tell-tales-sinks-depp-pirates/102172340/ |archivedate=June 8, 2017 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/entertainment-arts-13475908 |title=BBC News \u2013 Mark Kermode savages new Pirates Of The Caribbean film |last=Kermode |first=Mark |date=May 20, 2011 |work=BBC News |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110821022658/http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/entertainment-arts-13475908 |archivedate=August 21, 2011 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.azcentral.com/thingstodo/movies/articles/2011/05/18/20110518review-pirates-caribbean-stranger-tides-goodykoontz.html |title='Pirates of the Caribbean: On Stranger Tides,' 2 stars|last=Goodykoontz |first=Bill |date=May 18, 2011 |work=azcentral.com}}</ref> ''Pirates of the Caribbean'' is noted for reinvigorating the pirate film genre after decades of either no pirate films or failed pirate films.<ref>{{cite book |url=https://books.google.com/?id=U0N6AgAAQBAJ&pg=PT23&lpg=PT23&dq=pirates+of+the+caribbean+credited+with+bringing+back+the+pirates+genre#v=onepage&q=pirates%20of%20the%20caribbean%20credited%20with%20bringing%20back%20the%20pirates%20genre&f=false |title=Pirates in the Media |last=Hamilton |first=John |publisher=ABDO Publishing Company |date=January 10, 2007|isbn=9781617843198 }}</ref> The success of the series saw Disney and Jerry Bruckheimer try to replicate the franchise's success by releasing films such as ''[[Prince of Persia: The Sands of Time (film)|Prince of Persia: The Sands of Time]]'' and ''[[The Lone Ranger (2013 film)|The Lone Ranger]]'', the latter of which directed by Gore Verbinski. Both films were critical and commercial failures.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://articles.latimes.com/2010/may/24/entertainment/la-et-boxoffice-sidebar-20100524 |work=Los Angeles Times |title='Prince of Persia' weaker than hoped for in foreign debut |date=May 24, 2010}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/prince_of_persia_sands_of_time/ |title=Prince of Persia: The Sands of Times reviews at Rotten Tomatoes |work=Rotten Tomatoes |accessdate=2010-06-09}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/the_lone_ranger/ |title=''The Lone Ranger'' (2013) |work=[[Rotten Tomatoes]] |accessdate=28 July 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Shaw |first=Lucas |title='The Lone Ranger' to Cost Disney $160\u2013$190M in Q4 |url=https://www.thewrap.com/movies/article/lone-ranger-cost-disney-160-190m-q4-earnings-108876 |accessdate=7 August 2013 |work=The Wrap |date= August 6, 2013}}</ref>\n\n=== Accolades ===\n{{Main|List of accolades received by the Pirates of the Caribbean film series}}\n\n==== Academy Awards ====\nTogether, the first three films were nominated for a total of 11 [[Academy Awards]], of which a single award was won.\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"margin:left;\"\n|-\n! style=\"width:214px;\" rowspan=\"2\"| Award\n! colspan=\"5\" | Film\n|-\n! ''The Curse of the Black Pearl''\n! ''Dead Man's Chest''\n! ''At World's End''\n! ''On Stranger Tides''\n! ''Dead Men Tell No Tales''\n|-\n| '''[[Academy Award for Best Actor|Best Actor]]'''\n| {{nom}}<ref name=\"Oscars2004\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.oscars.org/awards/academyawards/legacy/ceremony/76th-winners.html |title=The 76th Academy Awards (2004) Nominees and Winners |accessdate=November 20, 2011 |work=oscars.org |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6BQv3CYAA |archivedate=October 15, 2012 |df= }}</ref><ref name=\"Oscar2004results\">{{cite web|url=http://www.blackflix.com/articles/76th.acad.winners.html |title=76th Academy Award Winners |work=Blackflix.com |accessdate=June 18, 2011 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110928165835/http://www.blackflix.com/articles/76th.acad.winners.html |archivedate=September 28, 2011 }}</ref><br />([[Johnny Depp]])\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|-\n| '''[[Academy Award for Best Production Design|Best Art Direction]]'''\n|\n| {{nom}}<ref name=\"Oscars2006\">{{cite web|url=http://www.oscars.org/awards/academyawards/oscarlegacy/2000-present/79nominees.html |title=Nominees & Winners for the 79th Academy Awards |publisher=[[Academy Awards]] |accessdate=June 18, 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110806185654/http://www.oscars.org/awards/academyawards/oscarlegacy/2000-present/79nominees.html |archivedate=August 6, 2011 |df= }}</ref>\n|\n|\n|\n|-\n| '''[[Academy Award for Best Makeup and Hairstyling|Best Makeup]]'''\n| {{nom}}<ref name=\"Oscars2004\" /><ref name=\"Oscar2004results\" />\n|\n| {{nom}}<ref name=\"Oscars2008\">{{cite web |url=http://www.oscars.org/awards/academyawards/legacy/ceremony/80th-winners.html |title=The 80th Academy Awards (2008) Nominees and Winners |publisher=Academy Awards |accessdate=June 18, 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111123183103/http://www.oscars.org/awards/academyawards/legacy/ceremony/80th-winners.html |archivedate=November 23, 2011 |df= }}</ref>\n|\n|\n|-\n| '''[[Academy Award for Best Sound Editing|Best Sound Editing]]'''\n| {{nom}}<ref name=\"Oscars2004\" /><ref name=\"Oscar2004results\" />\n| {{nom}}<ref name=\"Oscars2006\" />\n|\n|\n|\n|-\n| '''[[Academy Award for Best Sound Mixing|Best Sound Mixing]]'''\n| {{nom}}<ref name=\"Oscars2004\" /><ref name=\"Oscar2004results\" />\n| {{nom}}<ref name=\"Oscars2006\" />\n|\n|\n|\n|-\n| '''[[Academy Award for Best Visual Effects|Best Visual Effects]]'''\n| {{nom}}<ref name=\"Oscars2004\" /><ref name=\"Oscar2004results\" />\n| {{won}}<ref name=\"Oscars2006\" />\n| {{nom}}<ref name=\"Oscars2008\" />\n|\n|\n|}\n\n==== Golden Globe Awards ====\nTogether, all the four films were nominated for a total of 2 [[Golden Globe Award]]s, of which neither were won.\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"margin:left;\"\n|-\n! style=\"width:214px;\" rowspan=\"2\"| Award\n! colspan=\"5\" | Film\n|-\n! style=\"width:130px;\"| ''The Curse of the Black Pearl''\n! style=\"width:130px;\"| ''Dead Man's Chest''\n! style=\"width:130px;\"| ''At World's End''\n! style=\"width:130px;\"| ''On Stranger Tides\n! style=\"width:130px;\"| ''Dead Men Tell No Tales''\n|-\n| '''[[Golden Globe Award for Best Actor \u2013 Motion Picture Musical or Comedy|Best Actor in a Motion Picture \u2013 Comedy or Musical]]'''\n| {{nom}}<br />([[Johnny Depp]])\n| {{nom}}<br />([[Johnny Depp]])\n|\n|\n|\n|}\n\n==== Golden Raspberry Awards ====\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"margin:left;\"\n|-\n! style=\"width:214px;\" rowspan=\"2\"| Award\n! colspan=\"5\" | Film\n|-\n! ''The Curse of the Black Pearl''\n! ''Dead Man's Chest''\n! ''At World's End''\n! ''On Stranger Tides''\n! ''Dead Men Tell No Tales''\n|-\n| '''[[Golden Raspberry Award for Worst Actor|Worst Actor]]'''\n|\n|\n|\n|\n| {{nom}}<br />([[Johnny Depp]])<ref group=note name=pirates>Referred to as ''Pirates of the Caribbean XIII: Dead Careers Tell No Tales'' on [https://web.archive.org/web/20180130225712/http://www.razzies.com/razz-newz.html the official nomination list].</ref>\n|-\n| '''[[Golden Raspberry Award for Worst Supporting Actor|Worst Supporting Actor]]'''\n|\n|\n| {{nom}}<br />([[Orlando Bloom]])\n|\n| {{nom}}<br />([[Javier Bardem]])<ref group=note name=pirates />\n|-\n| '''[[Golden Raspberry Award for Worst Screen Combo|Worst Screen Combo]]'''\n|\n|\n|\n|\n| {{nom}}<br />([[Johnny Depp]] & his worn-out drunk routine)<ref group=note name=pirates />\n|}\n\n==== MTV Movie Awards ====\nTogether, all the first three films were nominated for a total of 13 [[MTV Movie Awards]], of which 4 were won.\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"margin:left;\"\n|-\n! style=\"width:214px;\" rowspan=\"2\"| Award\n! colspan=\"5\" | Film\n|-\n! style=\"width:130px;\"| ''The Curse of the Black Pearl''\n! style=\"width:130px;\"| ''Dead Man's Chest''\n! style=\"width:130px;\"| ''At World's End''\n! style=\"width:130px;\"| ''On Stranger Tides''\n! style=\"width:130px;\"| ''Dead Men Tell No Tales''\n|-\n| '''[[MTV Movie Award for Best Movie|Best Movie]]'''\n| {{nom}}\n| {{won}}\n| {{nom}}\n|\n|\n|-\n| '''[[MTV Movie Award for Best Performance|Best Male Performance]]'''\n| {{won}}<br />([[Johnny Depp]])\n| {{won}}<br />([[Johnny Depp]])\n|\n|\n|\n|-\n| '''[[MTV Movie Award for Best Performance|Best Female Performance]]'''\n|\n| {{nom}}<br />([[Keira Knightley]])\n| {{nom}}<br />([[Keira Knightley]])\n|\n|\n|-\n| '''[[MTV Movie Award for Best Breakthrough Performance|Best Breakthrough Female Performance]]'''\n| {{nom}}<br />([[Keira Knightley]])\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|-\n| '''[[MTV Movie Award for Best On-Screen Duo|Best On-Screen Team]]'''\n| {{nom}}<br />([[Johnny Depp]] & [[Orlando Bloom]])\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|-\n| '''[[MTV Movie Award for Best Villain|Best Villain]]'''\n| {{nom}}<br />([[Geoffrey Rush]])\n| {{nom}}<br />([[Bill Nighy]])\n|\n