e}}\n\n[[Category:Film series introduced in 2003]]\n[[Category:Fiction set in the 1740s]]\n[[Category:Fiction set in the 18th century]]\n[[Category:Comedy film series]]\n[[Category:Action film series]]\n[[Category:Films based on theme-park attractions]]\n[[Category:Pirates of the Caribbean (film series)| ]]\n[[Category:Disney film series]]\n", "name_user": "Ultimaniahk", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eOn Stranger Tides (20111):2011", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pirates_of_the_Caribbean_(film_series)"}
{"title_page": "List of presidents of France", "text_new": "{{short description|Wikipedia list article}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2015}}\n{{Politics of France}}\nBelow is a list of presidents of France. The first [[President of the French Republic]] is considered to be [[Napoleon III|Louis-Napol\u00e9on Bonaparte]] (later Napoleon III), who was elected in the [[1848 French presidential election|1848 election]], under the [[French Second Republic|Second Republic]]. The current officeholder has been [[Emmanuel Macron]] since 14 May 2017. He was elected in the [[2017 French presidential election|2017 election]].\n\n[[Jean Casimir-Perier]] spent the shortest time in office, resigning in 1895, six months and 20 days after taking office. Five other presidents of France resigned before the end of their term: [[Patrice de MacMahon, Duke of Magenta|Patrice de MacMahon]] in 1879, [[Jules Gr\u00e9vy]] in 1887, [[Alexandre Millerand]] in 1924, [[Ren\u00e9 Coty]] in 1959 and [[Charles de Gaulle]] in 1969. [[Fran\u00e7ois Mitterrand]] served the longest, nearly fourteen years from 1981 to 1995. Of the individuals elected as President of the French Republic, two died in office of natural causes ([[F\u00e9lix Faure]] and [[Georges Pompidou]]) and two were assassinated ([[Marie Fran\u00e7ois Sadi Carnot|Sadi Carnot]] and [[Paul Doumer]]).\n\n==French First Republic==\n{{detail|List of Presidents of the National Convention}}\nAfter the establishment of the [[French First Republic]] in 1792, the [[Separation of powers|three powers of the State]] were entrusted to the [[National Convention]], the unicameral parliament. The National Convention was led by a presidency, which rotated fortnightly. From 1793 the National Convention was dominated by its sub-committee, [[Committee of Public Safety]], in which the leading figures were [[Georges Danton]] and then [[Maximilien Robespierre]].\n\nAfter the [[9th Thermidor]], Robespierre and his followers were arrested and executed, and the National Convention was replaced by a \"[[Corps l\u00e9gislatif|Legislative Body]]\" divided in [[Council of Five Hundred]] (lower house) and [[Council of Ancients]] (upper house), while the executive power was taken by a [[French Directory|Directory]]. The Directory was officially led by a president, as stipulated by Article 141 of the [[Constitution of the Year III]]. An entirely ceremonial post, the first president was [[Jean-Fran\u00e7ois Rewbell]] who was chosen by lot on 2 November 1795. The directors conducted their elections privately, with the presidency rotating every three months.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.archontology.org/nations/france/directory_1795_99/ |title=France: Presidents of the Executive Directory: 1795-1799 |author=Cheynet, Pierre-Dominique |year=2013 |publisher=Archontology.org |accessdate=16 November 2013 }}</ref> The last president was Gohier.<ref name=LS199>Lefebvre & Soboul, p. 199.</ref> The leading figure of the Directory was [[Paul Barras]], the only director to serve throughout the Directory.\n\nIn 1799, the [[Coup of 18 Brumaire]] deposed the Directory in favor to General [[Napoleon Bonaparte]]. The parliamentarian [[Emmanuel Joseph Siey\u00e8s]] was a proponent of a new system of government for the Republic; the coup initially seemed certain to bring his system into force. The [[Constitution of the Year VIII]] establish a new government called [[French Consulate|Consulate]], composed by Bonaparte, [[Jean Jacques R\u00e9gis de Cambac\u00e9r\u00e8s|R\u00e9gis de Cambac\u00e9r\u00e8s]] and [[Charles-Fran\u00e7ois Lebrun, duc de Plaisance|Lebrun]] as first, second and third consuls, respectively. In 1804, the First Republic finally dissolved with the [[Coronation of Napoleon I|coronation of Napoleon Bonaparte]] as \"Emperor of the French\".<ref name=\"AndrewRoberts2\">{{cite book|author=Roberts, Andrew|title=Napoleon: A Life|publisher=Penguin Group|date=2014|page=355}}</\nCelestia ludenberg https://66.media.tumblr.com/d3d14e6c309aaa5f312de421888075fd/tumblr_inline_oj2behvzj31tzs2po_1280.png</ref>\n\n==List of officeholders==\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center\"\n|-\n! rowspan=\"2\" | N\u00b0\n! rowspan=\"2\" | Portrait\n! rowspan=\"2\" width=30% | Name{{efn|Including French honorifics.}}<br>{{small|(birth{{ndash}}death)}}\n! colspan=\"3\" width=30% | Term of office and election\n! rowspan=\"2\" width=25% | Political party\n! rowspan=\"2\" | {{Tooltip|Ref.|Reference}}\n|-\n! colspan=3 style=\"font-size:90%; line-height:normal\" | Previous office\n|-\n| colspan=\"8\" | \n===[[French Second Republic]] (1848{{ndash}}1852)===\n|-\n|- bgcolor=#FFFFE0\n| colspan=\"8\" | The Government of ''[[Jacques-Charles Dupont de l'Eure|Jacques-Charles Dupont]]'' deputised during the interim (24 February 1848 {{ndash}} 9 May 1848).\n|-\n|- bgcolor=#FFFFE0\n| colspan=\"8\" | The ''[[French Executive Commission (1848)|Executive Commission]]'' deputised during the interim (10 May 1848 {{ndash}} 24 June 1848).\n|-\n|- bgcolor=#FFFFE0\n| colspan=\"8\" | The Government of ''[[Louis-Eug\u00e8ne Cavaignac]]'' deputised during the interim (28 June 1848 {{ndash}} 20 December 1848).\n|-\n! rowspan=\"2\" style=\"background:{{Bonapartist/meta/color}}; color:black;\" | 1\n| rowspan=\"2\" | [[Image:Mayer and Pierson - Napol\u00e9on III. (Zeno Fotografie) (cropped).jpg|100px]]\n| rowspan=\"2\" align=\"center\" | '''[[Napoleon III|Louis-Napol\u00e9on Bonaparte]]'''<br/>{{small|[[Legion of Honour|GCLH]]}}<br/>(1808{{ndash}}1873)\n| 20 December 1848\n| 2 December 1852\n| [[1848 French presidential election|{{smaller|1848}}]]\n| rowspan=\"2\" | [[Bonapartist]] \n| rowspan=\"2\" | <ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.elysee.fr/president/la-presidence/le-president-de-la-republique/histoire-des-presidents-de-la-republique/louis-napoleon-bonaparte-1808-1873.5531.html |title=Louis-Napol\u00e9on Bonaparte (1808\u20131873) |publisher=Official website of the French Presidency |language=French |accessdate=2 August 2010 |url-status=dead